<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Traffic Departments Urged to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A South African
organization grouping motoring broadcasters and journalists
has called on the traffic authorities to sustain a campaign
which has been launched to cut the road deaths toll during
the Christmas holiday period.
</P>
<P>
The Transport Department has launched "Arrive Alive" campaign
since October last year. The four-month campaign, designed to be
ended this month, is said to have reduced the road carnage by
about 400 so far.
</P>
<P>
"The sad part is that the campaign is now over and the
situation on our roads is very likely to return to its normal
unacceptable state until the holiday campaign is launched," said
Ian Auret, Chairman of the Committee for Active Road Safety,
today.
</P>
<P>
"If we are to attain success in curbing the carnage on our
roads, a campaign like Arrive Alive needs to be ongoing," Auret
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest reports by the traffic authorities,
the death toll on South African roads since December 1 last year
had risen to 1021, most of them passengers and pedestrians.
</P>
</TEXT>
