<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Army Deployed to Quell Riots in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government
deployed an unspecified number of army members in Harare
today while others were put on standby to help stop riots which
have been rocking the capital since Monday.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa told a press conference
the army will not hesitate to shoot trouble markers.
</P>
<P>
This is not a state of emergency, he said, but a move by the
government to stop further looting and damage to property by
rioters.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts estimated the cost of damage and loss
of property caused by the riots on Monday alone to 70 million
Zimbabwean Dollars (four million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The riots which were mainly confined to high density areas
had spread to low income areas by
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the army is meant to complement the efforts
being made by the police whose 300 support unit members are
battling to control the situation.
</P>
<P>
"We felt that we should take additional measures to control
the rampant looting and hooliganism in the demonstrations, and
because of the deteriorating situation," Dabengwa said.
</P>
<P>
"The army is not trained to use baton sticks, the army carries
guns and live ammunition, and they will not hesitate to shoot any
people who are trouble makers and want to engage in looting," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations were sparked by an average
increment of 20 percent on almost all basic commodities with the
private sector blaming the increases on the devaluation of the
Zimbabwean Dollar, high interest and inflation rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
