<HEADLINE> Harare's Riots Enter Second Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The riots in Harare entered the
second day today despite the Zimbabwean government
announced that the price hike of mealie-meal by 21 percent
intended to be effected on Monday had been reversed.
</P>
<P>
The government also said it was going to review prices of all
commodities.
</P>
<P>
The riots were sparked by a recent increment by an
average 20 percent on basic commodities due to the devaluation of
the Zimbabwean Dollar, high interest rates hovering around 41
percent and the high inflation rate which currently is above 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
The situation began relatively quiet today in most suburbs. But by
mid-morning, riots started again in some suburbs particularly
Mbare, the poorest and volatile suburb on the southern edge of
the city centre where rioters continued to battle police and
looted the shops.
</P>
<P>
In other suburbs such as Marren Park and the dormitory town of
Chitungwiza, riots which had died down resumed around mid-morning
today.
</P>
<P>
Riots which had been confined to Harare's high density
suburbs spread to low density areas today, prompting police to
mount a heavy presence on almost all major roads leading into the
city center.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts estimated today that the capital could have
lost 70 million Zimbabwean Dollars (four million U.S. Dollars)
worth of business due to continuing food riots which first broke
out on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the city's low-income suburbs, almost all shops were looted
and burnt by angry mobs yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
