<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Trade Surplus Surges to Nearly $65 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany's trade surplus surged to
118.6 billion marks (64.5 billion U.S. dollars) in the first
eleven months of 1997, which was already a new record since the
1990 German reunification, the German Federal Statistics Office in
Wiesbaden announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures released the statistics office,
Germany's exports in the first eleven months of 1997 totaled
809.3 billion marks (439.8 billion dollars), up 12.7 percent from
the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the country's imports also increased by 10.1 percent
to total of 690.7 billion marks (375.4 billion dollars) during the
same period.
</P>
<P>
In November of 1997 alone, Germany's exports expanded by 12.4
percent over the level of a year ago to 79.3 billion marks (43
billion dollars) while imports growing by 9.9 percent to 66.2
billion marks (36 billion dollars), so that the country's trade
surplus was 13.1 billion marks (7.1 billion dollars) in November.
</P>
<P>
The country's record trade surplus of 134 billion marks was
achieved in West Germany in 1989. After the German reunification,
the largest trade surplus was 107 billion marks in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the latest expansion in trade surplus, Germany's
current account, which includes trade both in goods and services,
also swung back to a surplus of 2.6 billion marks (1.4 billion
dollars) in November from a deficit of 4.4 billion marks (2.4
billion dollars) recorded in October.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first eleven months of 1997 as a whole, the
country's current account deficit was still 8.8 billion marks (4.8
billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
