<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Warns of Introduction of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today warned that the government would be forced to
introduce a state of emergency in the country if present food
riots continue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to journalists, Mugabe blamed the riots on the
opposition political parties which he accused of taking advantage
of the current economic hardships.
</P>
<P>
"Those behind the riotous demonstration should be warned that
the government does not want to impose strict rules," he said,
adding that there was no reason for people to resort to
demonstrations in a riotous manner as everyone was affected by
the current economic hardships.
</P>
<P>
"If they continue this trend we will become a violent nation
and all efforts we have been trying to inculcate to the nation as
values will be lost," he said, adding "we cannot, as government,
allow this to continue. We cannot allow hooliganism to continue."
</P>
<P>
He revealed that his cabinet will be meeting soon to look at
the prevailing situation.
</P>
<P>
The riots started on Monday in Harare in protests against the
steep increases in the prices of basic commodities, which follows
the fall of the Zimbabwean Dollar against other major currencies.
The prices of basic commodities have gone up by an average of 20
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
