<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mutual Funds in Canada Continue to Draw Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Canadian investors continued to
pour a record amount of money into mutual funds last year despite
market volatility.
</P>
<P>
The latest figure shows that Canadians contributed a record
52.3 billion dollars (36.6 billion USD) in new money in mutual
funds in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This has boosted the country's mutual fund industry's assets to
283.2 billion dollars, according to the Investment Funds Institute
of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The activity far outpaced the year of 1996, when mutual funds
attracted 41 billion dollars in new money.
</P>
<P>
In December 1997, Canadians invested three billions in new
investment in mutual funds despite the Asian financial crisis and
its impact on world market.
</P>
<P>
That was down from November's net sales of 4.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The institute said that about 70 percent of the new money
invested in 1997 was put into equity mutual funds, with the
reminder going into bond, money-market and mortgage funds.
</P>
<P>
"Money will continue to flow into mutual funds because there
really isn't another alternative for a return of between eight and
nine percent," a research with the institute was quoted as saying
by reports Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
