<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jospin Rules Out Immediate Overall Raise of Welfare Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin Tuesday ruled out an immediate and overall raise of minimum
unemployment aid, because he said the government simply could not
afford it.
</P>
<P>
"All is not possible, immediately," said Jospin when
answering questions at the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
But Socialist Party officials have hinted that the government
is considering releasing some packages of social aid frozen by the
former rightwing government, and providing three to four billion
francs of emergency aid to long-time unemployed people.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government is under increasing pressure from the
unemployed, unions, the Communist Party and some other left
parties within the majority for a raise of minimum unemployment
aid, which now stands only at 1,500 francs (300 U.S. dollars) a
month.
</P>
<P>
But the government said it would cost 60 billion francs (10
billion U.S. dollars) and would destroy the budget designed for
joining the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
Jospin also rejected a request by the unemployed and unions for
a special aid for the young unemployed under 25, which he said
would cost an extra 10 billion francs (167 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"We cannot increase the deficit of 70 billion francs... Nor
can we ask the French people to support it," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
