<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Netanyahu Start Talks on Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Tuesday hoped to make some progress on Middle East peace process
in his talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
"We're going to have a good-faith, detailed, frank discussion
and do our best to make some progress, and I think we've got the
chance to do that," Clinton said at a photo session with
Netanyahu at the White House before their talks.
</P>
<P>
Clinton would focus his discussions with Netanyahu on the
peace process that has been deadlocked since last March, and
large part of the discussions would be on Israel's redeployment
at the West Bank in an accordance with Oslo interim agreements
signed in 1993 by the former Israeli Labour government and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who arrived in Washington last night, just
repeated his long-standing position, saying any withdrawal of
the Israeli troops from the West Bank should "ensure our
defenses."
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Israeli prime minister would bring a very
modest pullback offer to Clinton, who has been pressuring Israel
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
It is the sixth meeting between Clinton and Netanyahu and
political analysts expected no dramatic breakthrough the meeting
would bring to the currently moribund peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
