<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Heathrow Mortar Attack Trial Opens in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A man accused of helping IRA
bombers launch a mortar attack against Heathrow Airport went on
trial in London on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Michael Gallagher allegedly provided "vital support to the
bombers", but he denies charges of conspiring to cause explosions
and "making a contribution towards acts of terrorism" in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The court heard that the mortar bombs were packed with plastic
explosive but the detonators failed to trigger the blast.
</P>
<P>
However, that was not what IRA commanders had intended to
happen when they gave the orders for three salvoes to be fired,
prosecution lawyer Richard Horwell said.
</P>
<P>
"That they were intended to explode is beyond doubt," he told
Woolwich Crown Court in southeast London.
</P>
<P>
"They were packed with high-performance plastic explosive and
the contained detonators...It is plain that at the very least
widespread destruction to property was intended," Horwell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
