<HEADLINE> Leaders From 13 African Countries to Meet in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- State and government leaders
from 13 eastern and southern African countries are to meet in
Kampala on January 23 and 24 to discuss economic development in
the region, Hope Kwengere, Press Secretary to the Ugandan president,
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The summit will discuss crucial issues concerning economic
development in the region and to map out possible common
strategies for development, the press secretary said.
</P>
<P>
The discussions will focus on trade, investment,
infrastructure, development of human and institutional capacity,
public resources, conflict prevention and post conflict
reconstruction, he added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be attended by leaders from the Democratic
Republic of Congo, Tanzania, Rwanda, Eritrea, Zambia, Mozambique,
Senegal, Kenya, Zimbabwe, Ethiopia, Botswana, South Africa and
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
James Wolfensohn, the President of the World Bank, will also
attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders will arrive in the Ugandan capital on
January 23 morning. A joint press conference will be held at the
conclusion of the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
