<HEADLINE> Mandela to Open Lesotho Water Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will fly to Lesotho on Thursday to inaugurate a
giant water project supplying water to South Africa, the
president's office said today.
</P>
<P>
He will deliver an inaugural address at the ceremony at Muela
in northern Lesotho, and jointly commission the transfer of water
with Lesotho King Letsie III.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho highland water project, which took about 10
billion Rand (2.03 billion U.S. Dollars) and 11 years to
complete, was designed to provide much needed water to South
Africa while benefiting under-developed Lesotho with wanted funds
and hydro-electric power.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma, Botswana President Sir Ketumile
Masire, and South African and Lesotho Water Affairs Ministers
will also attend the ceremony at the Muela hydro-power complex,
in the heart of the enclave kingdom's mountain foothills.
</P>
<P>
However, Thursday's inauguration is overshadowed by untimely
rainstorms at the site in recent days. Downpours destroyed two
giant marquees intended to house 2,500 guests invited to the
ceremony, left the site ankle-deep in water and flooded the
underground hydro-electric power station.
</P>
<P>
It was somewhat ironical that the water flowing into Gauteng
Province, which usually suffers water shortage and was designed
the major recipient of the project's water, was now unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
As heavy rains unusual for this season of South Africa have
filled most water supply reservoirs of the province, some of the
incoming water is being diverted to other dams and rivers, local
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
