<HEADLINE> 1997 Sees Rise in Global Piracy Attacks: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of seamen killed last
year in increasingly violent pirate attacks around the world
doubled over the previous year to 51, according to a report
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, published by the UK International Maritime Bureau
(IMB), said that there were 229 pirate attacks in 1997, up from
188 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
More pirates are carrying guns and knives, the report said.
Last year, pirates carried guns on 68 occasions, up from 32 times
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"It's the brutality of the attacks and the fact that the
pirates are never caught which is causing us concern," said Eri
Ellen, executive director of the IMB.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that more than 400 crew members were taken
hostage during 1997, compared with 194 in 1996, and ships were
fired on 26 times, up from only six times in 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the attacks last year took place in the
following six countries: Indonesia, Thailand, Brazil, the
Philippines, Sri Lanka and India.
</P>
<P>
The report urged governments to clamp down on piracy and called
for better policing of the high seas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
