<HEADLINE> UNSCOM, Iraq Agreed to Meet on Missile Warheads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- In their first meeting,
Chief United Nations arms inspector Richard Butler and Iraq's
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz had agreed to hold technical
meetings on missile warheads related issues on the first of
February, UN spokesman Fred Eckhard said today.
</P>
<P>
"In their first meeting, Richard Butler and Tareq Aziz
discussed the procedures for the technical evaluation meetings on
the missile warheads, chemical and biological weapons. They agreed
the technical meetings on missile warheads related issues will
take place on the first day of February followed shortly
afterwards by the technical meetings on chemical weapons," Eckhard
said.
</P>
<P>
"Butler, the Executive Chairman of the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction, indicated that technical experts form China,
France, Russia, Germany, Britain and the United States will
participate in these meetings," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived in Iraq on Monday in a bid to save the
inspection regime which Baghdad had hampered.
</P>
<P>
The recent standoff between Iraq and UNSCOM began last week
when Iraq prevented a U.N. team headed by an American from
continuing its inspections of Iraqi sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
