<HEADLINE> GM Staff in Germany Agree to Less Pay to Save Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The 46,800 employees in General
Motors' German subsidiary Opel signed an accord with the company
Tuesday on less pay rise in exchange for no forced layoffs by the
end of 2002, said reports reaching here from Ruesselsheim.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to pay rise 1.25 percent lower than their fellow
workers in other companies for four years from 1998 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
In return, Opel is to use no-pain methods to curb 3,000 to
4,000 jobs at its main plant in Ruesselsheim, west of Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
Workers above the age of 50 will be retired with top-ups to
their pensions contributed by the U.S.-owned company, and
volunteers will b sought for shorter work weeks on reduced pay at
Opel's three plants.
</P>
<P>
The accord, which is expected to save Opel 40 million marks (22
million U.S. dollars) every year, is prompted by recent call by GM
president Louis Hughes for 20 to 30 percent reduction in staff at
GM plants in Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
