<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Tuesday Noon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 20 (Xinhua)--Wall Street Stocks rose this
morning as the recovery on foreign markets continued and some
major American companies reported strong profits despite the
economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
26.65 at 7,780.20, down from an early 32-point gain. Broader
measure were posting larger gains.
</P>
<P>
The encouraging performance came after the Asian stock markets
closed generally higher today, with share prices rising for a
fifth consecutive session in Japan as government ministers
reiterated Tokyo's commitment to economic stimulus measures.
</P>
<P>
U.S. markets were closed Monday for the federal holiday
honoring Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
Before the open today, Chase Manhattan and Citicorp, the
nation's two biggest banks, reported improved fourth-quarter
profits, saying their troubles in Asia were offset by strength in
other business.
</P>
<P>
Chase matched wide expectations in its profit gainings while
Citicorp exceeded forcests by a slim margin.
</P>
<P>
But J.P. Morgan, the No. 3 banking company, missed analyst
forecasts by a wide margin, reporting a 35 percent drop in
earnings.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 288.98 million
shares, down from Last Friday's busy pace.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 list was up 7.31 at 968.82 million
shares, and the NYSE composite index was up 3.80 at 507.47.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index was up 13.78 at 1,576.66, and the
American Stock Exchanges composite index was up 6.23 at 670.22.
</P>
</TEXT>
