<HEADLINE> Israeli Exports to Asia Fall in 4th Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli exports to the Far
East shrank by 200 million dollars, or 20 percent, in the fourth
quarter last year, largely due to the economic crisis spreading
across Asia, The Jerusalem Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report presented to the Knesset
(Parliament) by the Industry and Trade Ministry as saying that
Israel's exports to Far East last year declined by 1 percent to
3.644 billion dollars from 3.679 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Topping the list, food and agriculture exports fell by 22
percent last year, while diamond exports declined 12 percent, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset Economic Committee convened a meeting of trade
officials and Asian diplomats Monday to discuss Israeli-Asian
trade and economic relations in light of the Asian monetary
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Trade Ministry Director-General Dov Mishor told
the meeting that despite the International Monetary Fund speaks
of decreased growth in world trade during 1998, the Israeli
government is still predicting a 9 percent growth in exports to
Asia this year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Ambassador to Israel Ronarong Nopakun said he
expected Israeli defense industries to be heavily hit by the
ongoing economic crisis in Asia because some countries lack hard
currency to pay for the purchase of advanced weapons.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Manufacturers Association's Textiles Division head Yair
Rotlevy estimated that the Asian crisis could cause Israeli
industry to lose 1 billion dollars in total. He said, to South
Korea alone, Israeli exports could shrink by 260 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Korean bilateral trade topped 700 million dollars in
1996, and was expected to rise to 1 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky urged Israeli
companies not to lose faith in the Asian tigers. He said Israel
would not change policies toward Asia despite the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Trying to allay concerns of Israeli exporters, South Korean
Ambassador Eui Yong Chung also played down the long-term major
impact the Asian crisis might have on Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said, of Israel's 530 million dollar exports to South Korea
in the first 11 months of 1997, about 400 million dollars were
high-tech products exports. The remainder principally comprised
components destined for end products in South Korea and 15 million
dollars in diamonds.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see any major impact, rather it's a good time for
potential investors from Israel to look at expanding their
interests in the region," Chung said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Opposes Iranian Involvement in exploiting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of
Commerce William Daley has said that Iran should not be a
cooperation partner in exploiting the Caspian oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Daily News published here
Tuesday, Daley said that Washington takes such a stand because
there are no changes in the policies of the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
"Tehran continues to support terrorism, development of weapons
of mass destruction and so on," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official, accompanied by 64 businessmen, arrived here
Sunday on a four-day visit to Turkey aimed at furthering
U.S.-Turkish cooperation in the energy field.
</P>
<P>
"There are a lot of energy sources, such as Russia. We do not
see Iran being part of the (Caspian energy) equation," Daley said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that Daley is conveying to Ankara such
a message that the U.S. administration is opposed to any kind of
energy cooperation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
As an energy-starving country in the oil-rich Middle East
region, Turkey has to import oil and natural gas from neighboring
countries to meet its increasing demands.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has tried to cooperate with Iran in some oil and gas
projects, but it has met sharp criticism from the United States.
</P>
<P>
On which pipeline is the better choice to transport the
Caspian oil, Daley said that the planned Baku-Ceyhan (a southern
Turkish port) pipeline has its advantages.
</P>
<P>
This pipeline will not only help provide energy for Turkey,
but for the rest of the world, he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official, however, also said that his country is not
against the planned "Blue Stream" pipeline between Russia and
Turkey, which is under the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Turkey agreed in principle to buy the Caspian
oil and natural gas from Russia, annoying the United States, whose
oil companies are involved in the Caspian oil exploitation.
</P>
<P>
Daley and his delegation will leave Turkey on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
