<HEADLINE> Creditor Institutions Urged to Cancel Africa's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The visiting Archbishop of
Canterbury and Primate of the Church of England, Rev. George
Carey today urged creditor institutions to cancel Africa's heavy
burden of debt.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the diplomatic community at Africa hall here, Carey
said the suffering of the people of Africa is immense and the
west has a moral responsibility to find ways of reducing
substantially the crushing burden of debt which compromises the
economies of entire nations and sends millions to early graves.
</P>
<P>
Carey said more children would die unnecessary deaths before
the year 2000 as a result of the debt crisis that enslaves poor
countries today than were killed in a passage during the infamous
Atlantic slave trade.
</P>
<P>
''In 1997 the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
estimated that 21 million children would die before 2000 unless
the debt crisis is resolved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
''We need to work together to confront the crisis directly and
urgently so that the millennium can truly be seen to be a time
of new beginnings for this great continent of Africa,'' he said,
adding that if there is to be a solution to the problems, it will
eventually come at some moment when creditor institutions finally
agree decisively to forgive debt.
</P>
<P>
The external debt of African countries was 340.5 billion U.S.
Dollars in 1996 and African countries paid 24 billion US Dollars
in debt servicing in 1996 alone, according to the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA). 
</P>
