<HEADLINE> Lebanon Doubts Israeli Withdrawal Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri has denied that Syrian pressure prompted Beirut to take a
lukewarm stance toward Israeli offer of conditional withdrawal
from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"The resolution (of the U.N. Security Council) is clear. It
calls for an unconditional withdrawal, " Hariri said in an
interview with local newspaper Daily Star published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"If Israel is serious about implementing the resolution, then
why attach conditions?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has proposed that
after proper security guarantees from the Lebanese government,
Israel would be willing to implement the U.N. Resolution 425 and
pull out its troops.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's remarks were apparently in response to reports at home
and abroad that Lebanon cannot positively react to the Israeli
offer just because Syria does not allow it to do so.
</P>
<P>
Syria now has 40,000-strong troops in Lebanon. With specially
relations and common interests, the two countries insisted on
holding peace talks with Israel simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said that Lebanon has learned lessons from Palestinians'
experience in dealing with Israeliut the current one has to double
the effort to make peace because of a serious credibility crisis,
stemming from its handling of the Palestinian question and its
refusal to honor agreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They claim it is difficult to m is not so in Israel's
case," he added.
</P>
<P>
Syrian and Lebanese talks with Israel have been frozen since
Netanyahu came into power more than one and a half year ago. The
new Israeli prime minister was accused of refusing to recognize
the previous Labor government's promise to withdraw from Syrian
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said that if Israeli withdrawal offer from the south
that has been conveyed though the media is serious, then why
hasn't it been made through proper channels.
</P>
<P>
He noted that he had approached the Europeans and the
Americans to inquire whether they were asked to convey a
"concrete proposal" to Beirut, but both denied receiving anything
official.
</P>
<P>
"There is a sponsor for the peace process, the American
sponsor, and any overture has to come through that channel," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The premier urged Israel to rethink its strategy urgently if it
is serious about continuing the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
