<HEADLINE> Israeli Tourism Sinks 3 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 2.3 million tourists
visited Israel last year, a drop of 3 percent compared to 1996,
according to figures released Tuesday by the Central Bureau of
Statistics (CBS) and Tourism Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the decline was actually less than what had
been predicted, despite the three major suicide bombings attacks
in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem last year.
</P>
<P>
"The predictions had been for a catastrophe, but after all the
terror attacks this year, the number was more or less the same as
last year," ministry spokeswoman Orly Doron said.
</P>
<P>
The CBS said there had been a major decline in the number of
incoming tourists during the first half of 1996 following a series
of terror bombings launched early that year by Islamic
militants.
</P>
<P>
But this leveled off during the second half of 1996, and the
number of visitors remained stable through last year, it added.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Civil Aviation Authority found
that there was a 5 percent increase in the number of passengers at
Ben-Gurion Airport last year compared to 1996. This resulted fruthority report'
 that the number of passengers flying
charter lines increased by 17 percent, accounting for a market
share of 18.3 percent for these companies, while scheduled
airlines only increased their load by 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Israeli airline EL AL carried 38 percent of all passengers
last year, a drop from 39.6 percent from 1996. The leading
foreign carriers were Turkish Airlines, British Airways,
U.S. Tower Air, Lufthansa of Germany and TWA of the U.S., in that
order, the report added. 
