<HEADLINE> Israeli Youth Hostile Toward Arabs: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Forty-four percent of Israeli
youth believe Israeli Arabs should be stripped of at least some
of their rights, said a poll released here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted in early January by the Israel
Geocartography Institute among 400 Israel's high school pupils,
said that "19 percent of the respondents believe the Israeli
Arabs endanger the state security and should therefore be
expelled from Israel."
</P>
<P>
Among all the respondents, 18 percent said "the Israeli Arabs'
rights should be taken away because they do not serve in the
defense forces," while seven percent said "the Israeli Arabs do
not deserve to have equal rights in a Jewish state."
</P>
<P>
Thirty-two percent said they believe Israeli Arabs should have
equal rights, but 24 percent of them made this conditional on
their serving in the defense forces, the poll said.
</P>
<P>
Shmuel Abuav, head of the committee which commissioned the
poll, said the findings should serve as a warning to the
educational system in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The poll has caused angry reaction from Tourism Minister
Moshe Katsav, who on Tuesday described it as a racist attitude
toward Israeli Arabs, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his anger and concern for this kind of attitude,
Moshe said the Israeli Arabs are equal citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
