<HEADLINE> UAE Says It Supports UN Ban on Iraqi Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) remained firmly committed to the U.N. ban on smuggling of
Iraqi oil, the UAE's WAM news agency quoted a senior official as
saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has been implementing the decisions taken last year
which provide for confiscating any vessel breaking the U.N. ban,
UAE's Minister of Sate for Foreign Affairs Sheikh Hamdan Bin Zayed
al-Nahyan told WAM.
</P>
<P>
"We have already confiscated six vessels, whose shipments
were sold and the proceeds were credited to a special account,"
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The UAE Authorities will not be lax in implementing these
measures and ensuring full compliance with the U.N. resolutions,
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The statement came days after an oil barge sank off the UAE
coastline on January 7. The 11-member crew of the ill-fated
vessel were suspected of smuggling oil from iraq.
</P>
<P>
The crew members, including the Iraqi captian, an Egyptian
sailor and eight Philippine seamen are now kept in police custody
pending further investigation.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was banned from freely exporting oil after the
U.N. decided to impose economic sanctions against Baghdad for its
1990's invasion of kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Though Iraq was allowed to sell a limited number of oil worth 2
billion dollars every six months to get food and medicines in a
deal with the U.N. signed in 1996. But oil exports from Iraq are
strictly supervised by the U.N.. 
</P>
