<HEADLINE> Oman Calls for Urgent Oil Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Oman has called on the
members of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) to hold an urgent
meeting of oil ministers to discuss the issue of oil price slump
in the world market, the Omani News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There should be a meeting of GCC oil ministers to coordinate
stands to face the decline of the global oil price, and discuss
the best way to support the price and avert negative effects on
our economies," Omani Minister of Oil and Gas Mohammed al-Ramhi
said in an appeal to GCC states.
</P>
<P>
The alliance's members need to adopt a common strategy to help
shore up the oil price, which is falling drastically, he said.
</P>
<P>
The price of oil in world market has dropped to about 15 U.S.
dollars a barrel in recent weeks, the lowest level since mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
Oil Experts here have attributed the drop to the declined
demand of East Asia due to the current financial crisis, an
unusually warm winter in the northern hemisphere, the return of
Iraq to the oil market and the increase of output ceiling decided
by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries last November.
</P>
<P>
The economy of GCC states, namely Oman, Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Qatar and Kuwait, is seriously
reliant on oil exports, which account for nearly two thirds of
their annual revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
