<HEADLINE> AL Chief: Somalia Enters New Phase of Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General
Esmat Abdul Meguid Tuesday said Somalia has already started a new
phase toward restoring security and stability after long years of
crisis and difficulties, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting between the Somali faction leaders and Arab
Seven-man Committee in charge of following up the Somali crisis
here, Abdul Meguid said economic aid requested by the Somalis
should not become an obstacle to efforts to restore unity and
stability in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
He added that some Arab states have offered assistance via the
league to meet the Somali demand.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's meeting covered the latest developments in Somalia
after the Somali factions signed a reconciliation agreement, he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
After months of Egyptian brokerage, warring Somali factions
signed an agreement in Cairo on December 22, 1997 to end conflicts
and form a federal government in the Horn of Africa state for the
first time in more than six years of clan war.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo agreement calls for Somalia's independence,
integrity and security as well as holding a national
reconciliation conference in the central Somali city of Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
The Arab leader said the agreement has won the support of the
Seven-man Committee, which is composed of Egypt, Libya, Sudan,
Tunisia, Yemen, Mauritania and Djibouti. The permanent delegates
of Saudi Arabia and Kuwait to the Arab League attended Tuesday's
committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Two Arab League officials will accompany the Somali leaders to
Mogadishu on Thursday to discuss ways to implement the Cairo
agreement, said Abdul Meguid. He called it "premature" to discuss
dispatching an Arab force to secure the convocation of the Somali
reconciliation conference next month.
</P>
<P>
The 465-member conference, the biggest gathering of warring
factions in years, is supposed to set up a 13-member Presidential
Council to select a president and a prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Somali faction leaders began talks in Cairo on November 12 to
try to find a solution to their conflicts. At least three previous
agreements on ending the fighting, including the one signed in
Cairo on May 29, have proved unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
The factional fighting, combined with a 1992 famine, has
claimed about 300,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
