<HEADLINE> Jordan Forms Special Team to Investigate Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has appointed a special
team to investigate the murder of six Iraqis and two Egyptians in
Amman, a Jordanian official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The team has found two cars in the suburb of the capital, which
are suspected to be used by the murderers, Jordanian Minister of
State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawe told reporters after a
cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said that a diplomatic license has been found in one of the
cars, but he declined to give more details.
</P>
<P>
The victims, allegedly killed by four to five people with Iraqi
accent early Sunday, include Hikmet Al-Hijo, charge d'affaires at
the Iraqi Embassy in Jordan and an Iraqi millionaire who is
believed to have done business for Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Mutawe disclosed that an Iraqi delegation arrived here Monday
to look into the case. But he said that the delegation will not
participate in the investigation carried out by the Jordanian team.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials have claimed that Iraqi opposition was
involved in the assassination, which has been denied by Al Wefaq
or the Iraqi National Accord, a major Iraqi opposition movement in
Amman.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Jordan and Iraq became tense after Iraq
executed four Jordanians on charge of smuggling car parts last
December. Jordan recalled the charge d'affaires at its embassy in
Baghdad and expelled seven Iraqi diplomats in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
However, ties improved in late December after Iraq renewed
an agreement to sell oil to Jordan at prices below market levels.
</P>
