<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes "Sizable" Pullback by Israel from West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
called for a "sizable and credible" pullback by Israel from the
West Bank so that the peace process in the Middle East could be
pushed forward, State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was what Secretary of State Madeleine Albright would put
forward to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu during
their 90-minute talks, which was a meeting separate from the one
between President Bill Clinton and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
"We do believe that it needs to take place in a way that it
is credible, that the size needs to be significant," Rubin said,
but he provided no details of the scope the United States has in
mind.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the size the United States has demanded was
believed to be about 12 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But what Netanyahu could offer to Clinton during their
one-hour talks might be 9 percent of the land, far away from the
demand of the Palestinian leader Yasir Arafat, who has insisted
on 80 or 90 percent of the territory, and also half of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Before his talks with Netanyahu, Clinton indicated he was not
planning to pressure the Israeli leader on the issue of
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"I think what we ought to talk about is what both sides can
do now," he said at a photo session with Netanyahu, who arrived
in Washington last night to present his modest pullback offer.
</P>
<P>
His possible 9 percent pullback of the West Bank certainly
falls short of the Clinton administration's goal, not to say the
demand of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he will have "a detailed, frank, good
discussion" with the Israeli leader, "We are going to work hard
to make progress," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth time that Clinton met with Netanyahu.
Clinton, claiming to be the sponsor of the Middle East peace
process, has not been very happy with Netanyahu constantly
turning a deaf ear to U.S. repeated warning over Israel's moves
that were in contradiction with Oslo agreements.
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians
has suspended for over ten months because of Israel's decision to
build Jewish housing units in Arab East Jerusalem and refusal to
withdraw from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
After failures of U.S. mediations by its envoy Dennis Ross
and Albright, Clinton has to come out to deal directly with
Netanyahu and Arafat, whom Clinton will meet on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
