<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Banker Hails Success in Fiscal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Central Bank Governor
Paul Ogwuma said today the positive macro-economic development the
country witnessed between 1995 and 1997 is attributable to a
combination of fiscal discipline on the part ofs of one billion
Naira (about 13 million U.S. Dollars), the first time in several
years," he said.
</P>
<P>
A larger surplus of 37 billion Naira (about 463 million
Dollars) was recorded in 1996 while that of 33 billion Naira
(about 413 million Dollars) was achieved in 1997, the governor
told a policy seminar on the 1998 budget held here.
</P>
<P>
"Inflationary pressures moderated significantly from a high of
72.8 percent in 1995 to 29.3 percent in 1996 and 8.5 percent in
1997, while reasonable stability was achieved in interest and
exchange rates," he added.
</P>
<P>
Above all, the governor said, the growth of real gross
domestic product improved from 2.2 percent in 1995 to 3.3 percent
in 1996 and 3.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the efforts by the Central Bank to maintain
monetary stability has strongly complemented the government
fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Apex Bank would continue to make its best
endeavors to ensure the price and exchange rate stability were
maintained this year.
</P>
<P>
As part of the government efforts to tighten fiscal
discipline, 26 local distressed commercial and merchant banks
have been closed down in the country.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the start of the liquidation process, Ogwuma said
in the capital Abuja Monday that the liquidation of distressed
banks will enhance restoration of full viability and confidence
in the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
The governor also announced that the closed banks have been
put under police protection to prevent the loss of any
properties.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to sanitize the banking system, Nigeria shut down 282
ailing community banks in one operation last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
