<HEADLINE> Canadian Province Wants Cigarette Poison Listed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian province of British
Columbia (B.C.) has said that it wants cigarettes sold there to
have a detail list of poisons and health hazards on their
packages.
</P>
<P>
Legislation to this effect will be introduced soon, B.C. Health
Minister Joy MacPhail has announced.
</P>
<P>
The proposal represents the strongest warning in Canada and
perhaps the world, according to the country's leading newspaper
the Globe and Mail.
</P>
<P>
The list of diseases attributed to smoking include lung, month
and throat cancer, heart disease, cataracts, stomach ulcers, skin
damage and others.
</P>
<P>
"Consumers can get more information from a can of insect killer
that they do from cigarettes. There is something terribly wrong
with this picture and B.C. is going to make it right," the
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
The proposed legislation to impose the new labeling
requirements goes far beyond warnings required on cigarette
packages by Canada's federal government.
</P>
<P>
Under the federal law, Canadian-made cigarette packages must
devote about one-third of the main panels to one of the several
health warnings.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the B.C. government hired a law firm to
launch a class-action lawsuit against the tobacco industry for
health-related damages.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that cigarette smoking costs B.C. taxpayers 1.5
billion dollars (1.1 billion USD) and caused about 6,000 deaths
each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
