<HEADLINE> 2,372 Drug Traffickers Netted in Nigeria in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's drug control agency
announced today it arrested 2,372 suspects carrying hard drugs
last year, up from 1,187 in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17,683.12 kg of hard drugs were caught with the
suspects in 1997, a slight drop from 19,834.26 kg in 1996, the
National Drug Law Enforcement Agency (NDLEA) reported.
</P>
<P>
According to NDLEA chairman Maj.-Gen. Musa Bamaiyi, the 1997
arrests can be broken down into 2,143 persons for Indian
hemp-related offenses and 129 for illegal involvement with
psychotropic substances.
</P>
<P>
The other 60 and 40 persons were arrested for trafficking in
heroin and cocaine respectively, the chairman said at a news
briefing in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Bamaiyi said in 1997 heroin seizure accounted for 10.49 kg, a
drop from 19.37 kg in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Trafficking in cocaine would have continued to decline but for
30.51 kg intercepted when nine suspects tried to bring the drug
into Nigeria through neighboring Niger, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, once regarded as a drug transshipment center in west
Africa, has witnessed an increasing number of addicts of drugs,
mainly Indian hemp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
