<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Textile Industry to Face Fierce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's weaving industry is to
face fierce competition from foreign textiles which are at low
prices as the country lifted a ban on import of textile products
this month.
</P>
<P>
Egypt lifted the ban on January 1 to comply with World Trade
Organization (WTO) regulations, causing fear among local producers
that the move will expose them to unfavorable competition.
</P>
<P>
But Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has said the producers
have already been cautioned to strengthen their competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"We have warned textile firms that they must develop production
so that they can compete internationally, but they are still
slow," Mubarak said on television recently. "We are not going
to protect the industry forever."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he expressed belief that the Egyptian textile
industry is able to stand up to foreign competition after the
country opens its market.
</P>
<P>
The textile industry, one of Egypt's major foreign currency
earner, is witnessing low-level competitiveness due to higher
cotton price and lack of renovation.
</P>
<P>
The volume of textile exports slumped to 2.5 billion Egyptian
pounds (740 million U.S. dollars) in 1996 from 3 billion pounds
(880 million dollars) in 1995, according to a report by the
Egyptian Committee of Industrial Production and Energy.
</P>
<P>
But economists say that the industry will have a better future,
if it can get high-quality cotton and skilled labor, and lower its
cost.
</P>
<P>
When the Egyptian government lifted the ban on importing
textiles, it imposed an import tariff of 54 percent on textiles,
which is in line with WTO regulations allowing its members to levy
a 60 percent of tariff to be reduced by 3 percent a year from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO accord that took effect three years ago,
signatory members agreed to phase out all forms of restrictions
and barriers to open up their markets to foreign products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
