<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Install 2.8 Million Phones in 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- About 2.8 million new
phone lines would be installed in South Africa in the next five
years in one of the world's fastest telecommunications roll-out
programs, South African Telecommunications Minister Jay Naidoo
said today.
</P>
<P>
The new lines included 1.2 million pay-phones and 1.6 million
new lines in under-serviced areas, bringing telephone penetration
in economically qualified households in all provinces to over 50
percent, South African Press Association quoted the minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Schools, clinics, libraries, community centers and small
villages would be the priorities of the program, Naidoo said at
the launch of a digital enhanced cordless telecommunications
network at Sandfontein in North-West Province.
</P>
<P>
"According to our program, around 55 percent of these priority
customers will be connected within three years and 80 percent of
the small villages within four years," he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 21,000 community telephones had been installed and
more than 172 villages connected over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
A telephone service could allow the government to introduce
new services, such as distance learning and the Internet, to
remote parts of the country at an affordable cost, bringing power
of communication and knowledge there, Naidoo said.
</P>
<P>
North-West Premier Popo Molefe said at the launch that
effective communications systems were the key to the development
of any geographical area.
</P>
<P>
"If South Africa wishes to be globally competitive, it needs
to revolutionize its communications networks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Those historically forgotten people under apartheid were for
the first time being exposed to the benefits of mass and
individual communications systems, which would open a whole new
world to them, Molefe said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
