<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today called
for help from the world community, vowing to make "every
endeavor" to ensure that the escalating violence in Rwanda was
brought to an end.
</P>
<P>
The South African Foreign Ministry reiterated in a statement
its concern over the escalating violence in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-seven people were reportedly killed and 30 others
injured in violent attacks in the past two days in northwestern
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses claimed that members of Rwanda's former Hutu army
and the extremist Interahamwe Youth Militia were responsible for
an early-morning attack on a bus-load of workers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
They said the assailants ordered passengers on the bus to
divide themselves on ethnic lines into Hutus (the majority group
in Rwanda) and Tutsis. When the workers refused, the attackers
opened fire and set the vehicle on fire.
</P>
<P>
The South African government condemned such acts of senseless
violence in the strongest terms.
</P>
<P>
"It calls on the people of Rwanda and the international
community to isolate and refrain from assisting those involved in
such acts of violence and to ensure that they are brought to
justice," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
There was also a danger that the situation in Rwanda might
deteriorate to the point where the violence would again spill
over into neighboring countries, given that conflicts in the
region were closely interlinked, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
"It (South Africa) therefore appeals to the international
community to assist the Rwandan government in bringing the
violence to an end and constructing a democratic Rwanda in which
all its citizens can live in peace and harmony," the statement
added. 
</P>
