<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Israel Enhances Commercial, Trade Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Facing a collective economic
block by Arab neighbors, Israel has been enhancing commercial and
trade links with Cyprus, an island country just 400 kilometers
away across the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade stood at about 100 million U.S. dollars in
1996, Cyprus News Agency reported Tuesday, citing latest official
figures.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus exported a total of 15 million Cyprus pounds (about 30
million U.S. dollars) of goods to Israel in 1996, in variety of
fish, animal and vegetable fats, gypsum, fruit juice, tobacco
products, pharmaceutical products, plastics and plastic articles.
</P>
<P>
Domestic exports to Israel recorded a 35 percent increase in
the two years of 1995 and 1996 and re-exports an impressive 75
percent for the same period.
</P>
<P>
Israeli exports to Cyprus in 1996 reached 31 million pounds
(about 62 million dollars), including petroleums, chemicals,
machinery and plastics.
</P>
<P>
In the field of tourism, Cyprus has become a very popular
holiday destination for the Israelis and in 1997 more than 50,000
Israelis visited the island.
</P>
<P>
Louisa Varaclas, Director of the Cyprus Tourism Organization
(CTO) office in Tel Aviv, was quoted as saying that "Israelis like
travelling and although prices in Cyprus are not very cheap,
compared to other nearby destinations, they are prepared to pay
the extra cost for quality tourism."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus News Agency also quoted Cyprus' Commercial Attache in
Tel Aviv Eleni Pitsillides as saying that Cyprus' trade office in
Tel Aviv and exchange of visits by businessmen and trade ministry
officials have contributed a great deal toward increase trade.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been confronting an economic block by Arabs in
protest against its occupation of their lands for decades. Cyprus
and Israel signed in 1994 a general trade agreement to promote
bilateral trade and facilitate participation in each other's
fairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
