<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Committee to Meet on Travelers Cheque </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The ECOWAS Ad-Hoc Committee on
Monetary Questions is to meet early next month to review issues
connected with the implementation of the ECOWAS travelers cheque.
</P>
<P>
The committee is working toward a single currency for the
sub-region by the year 2000, one of the main objectives of the
16-member Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) set
to lead to economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The committee would evaluate the reservations of some member
states which stalled last month's launching of the scheme, said
ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate, quoted by the News
Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The Central Banks of eight Francophone member states -- Benin,
Burkina Faso, Cote d'Ivoire, Guinea Bissau, Niger, Mali, Senegal
and Togo -- frustrated the December 4 launching at the last
minute, insisting other member states, including Liberia, pay up
arrears owed them before the take-off.
</P>
<P>
They also called for the involvement of commercial banks,
preferably Ecobank, in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
But Kouyate dismissed the later request, pointing out that the
Southern African Development Commission had implemented a similar
scheme with the inspiration of ECOWAS without such involvement.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the February 6 meeting in Abuja will find
solutions to these problems," added the former United Nations
official, who became the scribe of the sub-regional economic bloc
at the ECOWAS summit last August.
</P>
<P>
The ad-hoc committee is made of Cote d'Ivoire, Ghana, Mali,
Nigeria and Togo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
