<HEADLINE> Egypt, US, France Contact on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Tuesday received two phone calls from U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine on the latest Mideast peace developments.
</P>
<P>
Moussa described the two conversations as having covered
"extremely important topics" and that he kept Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat updated.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, at the end of his two-day visit to Egypt, left here
Tuesday morning for Paris to drum up support of the European
leaders before his meeting Thursday with U.S. President Bill
Clinton in Washington in a make-or-break attempt to save the
faltering peace process.
</P>
<P>
Clinton held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Tuesday in the White House.
</P>
<P>
"Arab and European countries display considerable interest in
the peace drive developments and hope the Washington meetings
would come up with results likely to get the peace train back on
track," said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
"Albright assured me that the U.S. would be quite serious
during the Washington meetings with Arafat and Netanyahu and that
the American stance would be crystal-clear toward the current
peace conditions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa disputed the idea of crafting a new agreement between
the Palestinians and Israelis, saying that "there is only one Oslo
(convention) and there is no amendments thereto."
</P>
<P>
"Oslo (convention) is Oslo: You can either take it all or leave
it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli policy has paralyzed the peace drive, said Moussa,
calling on the U.S. to give a push to the talks on the Palestinian
track on the bases of land-for-peace formula.
</P>
<P>
"Although all indicators are pessimism-inspiring about the
Israeli stance, we still cherish the hope that the American stance
would rescue the peace drive and face up to the Israeli
expansionist policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. reportedly wants Israel to withdraw from more West
Bank territory and freeze Jewish settlements, and wants the
Palestinians to crack down harder on violence as a prelude to
jump-starting talks on a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of his Cairo visit, the Palestinian leader warned
that if the peace process failed, the Palestinians would be open
to all options, including a return to Palestinian uprisings in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which has helped mediate between Israelis and the
Palestinians, has repeatedly urged the Clinton administration to
force its Israeli ally to honor the signed peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab officials and commentators see the talks in
Washington as a last chance to break the 10-month-old impasse and
demand that Washington induce Israel to modify its hard line
policy on peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
