<HEADLINE> Lebanese Parliament Begins Debate on 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Parliament Tuesday
began a debate on the 1998 budget, which a number of parliament
members (MP) have vowed to vote against due to two contentious
topics.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget proposes that road taxes and car registration
fees be increased by six times as much as the existing level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it outlines a plan to issue treasury bonds of up to
2 billion U.S. dollars abroad to cover internal debt, which has
reached 12 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two proposals are aimed at keeping the 1998 budget deficit
below 40 percent to avoid last year's deficit of 59 percent, 22
percent higher than the expected.
</P>
<P>
But they have sparked strong criticism from opposition and
independent deputies.
</P>
<P>
MP and former prime minister Salim Hoss said issuing bonds
abroad will bring about negative results, and that increasing car
registration fees will widen the gap between the rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his readiness to vote against the budget.
</P>
<P>
MP Sami al-Hatrib criticized the government for spending money
only in the construction of airport or news conference center,
instead of improving people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
He said issuing the bonds can not radically improve the
money-strapped economic situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Sees Record Exports in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian exports set a record
last November rising by 1.5 percent to 25.6 billion Canadian
dollars (16.6 billion U.S. dollars), Statistics Canada said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite a 0.9 percent decline, imports remained near record
levels at 24.5 billion Canadian dollars (17.8 billion
U.S. dollars), the agency said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Canada's trade balance rose to 1.03 billion
dollars (750 million U.S. dollars) from 432 million Canadian
dollars (315 million U.S. dollars) in October.
</P>
<P>
In November, Canada exported more industrial goods, forest
products and consumer goods, and less machinery and equipment.
</P>
<P>
"The strong performance of industrial goods exports in November
was due to a jump in exports of precious metal (gold), mostly to
Hong Kong," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
On the import front, Canada bought from its trade partners less
machinery and equipment, automobile products and industrial goods,
which were the main factors for the 0.9 percent slide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
