<HEADLINE> Greece Wants Committees of Experts to Continue with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos said today that Athens wanted the Greek-Turkish
committees of experts to continue their contact conditionally.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Pangalos said that his country
would put forward the issue of the committees of experts at next
Monday's General Affairs Council, underlining that Greece believed
the process should continue under two conditions, namely the
preservation of its European Dimension and the need for
encouraging signs from Turkey regarding a meeting between the
members of the two countries which would be "of a procedural
nature."
</P>
<P>
He complained that from the beginning, Greece insisted that the
experts should focus on the procedural aspect of differences
between the two countries, but Turkey wanted "substantial talks on
all issues."
</P>
<P>
It was very important for the two countries to agree on the way
in which each dispute would be settled in the event that they
disagreed during their talks, he added.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the European Union (EU), Greece and Turkey set
up the committees of experts in May last year in order to review
procedural aspects of efforts to resolve their disputes.
</P>
<P>
The committees of experts had exchanged memorandums and replies
through the EU, But, in fact, the contact between the committees
has been frozen following the deterioration of Greek-Turkish
relations late last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister also stressed that Turkey should have
recourse to the international court at the Hague if it questioned
the ten-mile limit of Greek air space.
</P>
<P>
As for the extension of Greece's territorial waters from the
current six to twelve miles, he said that Greece had the right to
do so in accordance with the provisions of the law of the Sea
Convention, but Greece would do it "in a responsible manner as a
major sea power." 
</P>
</TEXT>
