<HEADLINE> IBM Earnings Jump in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- World giant computer maker
International Business Machines Corp. (IBM) posted a 3.3 growth in
revenue and a 4.09 percent jump in net income in 1997, according
to figures released by the company on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Total revenue stood at 78.5 billion U.S. dollars against 75.95
billion dollars for 1996, while net income reached 6.1 billion
dollars compared to 5.86 billion dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
IBM chief executive officer Louis Gerstner called the results
"especially satisfying" in the face of a negative currency impact
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Fourth-quarter revenue in 1997 rose 3.6 percent to 23.7 billion
dollars from 23.1 billion dollars a year earlier, IBM interim
chief financial officer Lawrence Ricciardi said after the New
Stock Exchange closed on Tuesday..
</P>
<P>
The computer-services business was again IBM's growing
engine, with revenue up 18 percent to 5.9 billion dollars in the
fourth quarter, while computer hardware sales fell 1 percent to
11.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ricciardi said North American sales of IBM products were up 9
percent, but European sales fell 4 percent and the Asia Pacific
market was flat at 4.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
IBM estimated that the Asian financial crisis caused it a 10
percent revenue loss in the region in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
IBM computer sales slowed down in Japan, but Australia and
China remained strong markets, Ricciardi said.
</P>
<P>
IBM's first quarter profit in 1998 is expected to fall short of
a year ago because of the continued negative impact of s strong
dollar and weak market in some Asian countries, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
