<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Nail Down New Airport Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 21 (Xinhua) --- A scheme of airport charges
for the newly built Hong Kong International Airport at Chek Lap
Kok will be gazetted on Friday, the Airport Authority (AA)
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The scheme will comprise three charges -- a landing charge, a
parking charge and a terminal building charge (TBC), said the AA,
which is responsible for the construction and operation of the
Hong Kong International Airport at Chek Lap Kok. The new airport
is scheduled to go into operation on July 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The charges represent, in aggregate, an increase of about 20
percent over those at Hong Kong's existing international airport
at Kai Tak, said a press release by the AA Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In determining the structure of these charges, the AA has taken
 care to ensure that charges are simple, non-discriminatory and
based on "user pays" principle, and that they are comparable with
those at other major international airports.
</P>
<P>
Capable of running round the clock in all weather, the new
airport will provide greater capacity and operational flexibility,
 and a wider choice of world-class facilities than Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
The AA estimates that the total revenue from airport user
charges for the financial year 1998-1999 will account for 37
percent of its total commercial and aeronautical revenue.
</P>
<P>
"The proportion compares favorably with many other
international airports in the world," said the authority. The
average proportion was 64 percent for Asian airports, 44 percent
for Pacific airports, and between 50 and 60 percent for airports
in other regions, according to a survey conducted by the Airport
Council International in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The AA held eight rounds of consultations with local and
international airlines and freight operators during the period of
devising the scheme between February 1996 and October
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
