<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conditions Will "Kill" 53,000 S.Korean Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 21 (Xinhua) -- About 53,000 South Korean
companies will go bankrupt or out of business this year because of
high market interest rates and low economic growth imposed on the
country as a result of its financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a report on Wednesday, the Korea Institute of Finance
predicted that the country's economy will grow by 0.7 percent this
year, falling short of the 1 to 2 percent growth suggested by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) which is imposing constraints.
</P>
<P>
If the nation's economic growth reaches a mere 0.7 percent in
1998, the defaulted bill ratio will come to 0.75 percent with
market interest rates soaring to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The defaulted bill ratio indicates that 4,300 companies in the
country will go "belly-up" every month, bringing the total number
of business failures to 53,000 in 1998, a more than threefold
increase over 1997.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the 11th largest economy in the international
community, sustained the serious financial crisis because of the
failure of a slew of conglomerates, and bad loans of financial
institutions after late 1997. These saw saw the country's per
capita productivity down to 9,400 U.S. dollars from the previous
year's 10,548 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The nation's economic situation is expected to worsen this year
as, under an agreement reached with the IMF for rescue loans of 57
billion U.S. dollars, South Korea has to completely restructure
its economy. Closing ailing financial institutions and legalizing
mass layoffs are the harsh conditions tied to the rescue loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
