<HEADLINE> Swimming Giants Set for World Cup Hong Kong Leg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Swimming World Cup Hong
Kong '98, the second leg of this year's 186,000 US dollars World
Cup Short-course series, is scheduled for February 21 and 22 at
the Kowloon Park Swimming Pool, the organizers announced here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This year's series has attracted two more cities to become the
host and the event is extended to South America and the Oceania
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong meet, the fifth annually staged in a row, has
been postponed from the usual date of January so as to give way to
the world swimming championships staged in Perth, Australia
earlier this month. And to facilitate swimmers, Sydney has become
the designated host of the opening leg, for January 21-22, of the
World Cup series, according to a spokesman of the Hong Kong leg's
organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
The third leg is scheduled for February 25-26 in Beijing. The
World Cup Series then move on to Rio de Janeiro of Brazil,
Shefield of Britain, Malmo of Sweden, Gelsenkirchen of Germany,
Imperia of Italy and Paris of France.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong organizing committee has so far received entries
for participation from 20 national or regional swimming
associations -- 10 from Europe, two from Oceania, one each from
Africa and America and six from Asia. The organizers expected for
more entries by the deadline at February 6.
</P>
<P>
Each of the nine legs will have 34 events both for men and
women.
</P>
<P>
The four past Hong Kong World Cup meets had witnessed two new
short-course world records -- the men's 100 meters freestyle
record of 47.83 seconds set in 1994 by Russian Alexandre Popov and
the 31.11 seconds mark set in 1996 by China's Han Xue in women's
50 meters breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
The world marks were later recognized as new world records by
the sport's world governing body, the International Amateur
Swimming Federation.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup Hong Kong '98 is organized jointly by the
Provisional Unban Council and the Hong Kong Amateur Swimming
Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
