<HEADLINE> Public Order in Mongolia Worsening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, January 21 (Xinhua) -- About 24,700 criminal cases
occurred in Mongolia in 1997, a 10.2 percent rise over the
previous year, says the Chief Directorate of Police (CDP) of
Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The incidents caused a total property loss of 23.5 billion
togrog (about 29 million U.S. dollars), as well as leaving 1,132
people dead and 5,501 disabled, the government agency said in an
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Larceny, robbery, hooliganism, abuse of power and crime
committed by military personnel were on the rise. Larceny
accounted for 54.1 percent of the cases.
</P>
<P>
Since the transition of the social system in the early 1990s,
Mongolia has been plagued by economic difficulties. Criminal
cases have proliferated because of widespread unemployment and
poverty and 66 percent of the criminals are jobless, official
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with leading senior police, judiciary and procuratorial
organs last year, Mongolian President Nachagyn Bagabandy called
for tougher action to combat crime and restore social stability.
</P>
<P>
An anti-larceny commission was set up for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
Police solved 86.2 percent of the criminal cases last year, 2.2
percent more than in 1996, the CDP said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
