<HEADLINE> Russia to Send 60 Inspectors to Iraq, Says Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia plans to send 60 experts
to join the international inspectors monitoring Iraq's program of
dismantling weapons of mass destruction, a Russian diplomat said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Russian Ambassador to Egypt Vladimir Gudev made the statement
following a meeting Wednesday with Egyptian Assistant Foreign
Minister for Arab and Middle East Affairs Sayyed Abu Zeid.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reviewed steps taken by the Russian side to improve
the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) missions, which
have been stranded again over the composition of the UN arms
inspection team, Gudev said.
</P>
<P>
"Among those steps is a proposal of sending 60 Russian experts
to take part in the international inspectors," he said, adding
that Russia has proposed to dedicate a reconnaissance plane to be
used by the commission.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said Russia's proposals have won wide approval
and voiced hope that other states would take part in the mission
to "increase the effectiveness" of the commission.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, complaining there are too many Americans in the team, has
threatened to cut off cooperation with the U.N. inspectors if the
inspections are not completed by May 20.
</P>
<P>
"Although the Russian proposals are not at Iraq's direct
request, yet they go in line with the stance of Iraq and a large
number of other states such as China and France," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abu Zeid told reporters that his meeting with Gudev also dealt
with the latest developments of the Iraq-U.N. standoff as well as
Russia's view on the Washington's recent efforts to broker an end
to the Mideast peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the Russian and Egyptian diplomats came as
chief U.N. inspector Richard Butler failed in his latest bid to
get Iraq's approval to have his arms monitors inspect the
presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is pushing an end to the crushing U.N. economic sanctions
imposed after it's 1990 invasion of Kuwait, which can not be
lifted until the inspectors say Iraq has eliminated its long-range
missiles, chemical and biological weapons and the means to produce
them.
</P>
<P>
In November, Iraq threw Americans on the U.N teams out of the
country. The U.N. withdrew the rest of the inspectors until Russia
brokered a deal three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
Last week the dispute flared again, with Iraq failing to
provide the necessary escorts for an inspection team led by an
American. 
</P>
</TEXT>
