<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Election Commission Bans Publication of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 21 (Xinhua) -- India's Election Commission
Wednesday banned for two weeks from February 14 publication and
broadcast of opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
It also put similar restrictions on exit polls from February 16
to 28.
</P>
<P>
The 12th Lower House of Parliament general elections are to be
held from February 16 to March 7 in four phases.
</P>
<P>
Announcing guidelines for publication and dissemination of
results of opinion and exit polls, Chief Election Commissioner Dr.
M.S. Gill made it clear that no result of any opinion poll could
be published or broadcast during the specified fortnight.
Contravention of the guidelines could be treated as a penal
offense punishable with imprisonment up to two years or with fine
or both.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Election Commission had arrived at the
decision after consulting 43 recognized political parties, most of
whom favored such restrictions. It was strongly felt that voters
should be left alone for a while to cast their ballot according to
their best judgment. Such dissemination, particularly on the eve
of polls or when the polling process is in progress, has the
potential to influence the electors when they are in the mental
process of making up their minds to vote or not to vote for a
certain political party or a candidate.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission also stipulated that those conducting
opinion or exit polls while publicizing it must indicate the
sample size of the electorate covered and geographical spread of
survey. They must give the details of methodology followed, likely
percentage of errors, the professional background and experience
of the organization and the key professionals involved in the
conduct and analysis of the polls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
