<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Meets British Foreign Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of
China, met here Wednesday with British Secretary of State for
Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
Tung exchanged views on a wide range of issues of common
interest with Cook, who arrived here Tuesday after a trip to
Beijing on January 19-20.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Tung told Cook that the "one country, two
systems" policy had been successfully implemented in Hong Kong
since it returned to China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Central People's Government is determined to ensure that
the principle of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" with a "high
degree of autonomy" is fully implemented, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the regional financial turmoil, Tung told Cook that Hong
Kong was fully committed to maintaining the linked exchange rate
between the Hong Kong dollar and the U.S. dollar and he believed
that Hong Kong will be the first one to bounce back from the
financial crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive said that elections to the first
Legislative Council of the HKSAR would be open, fair and honest.
"We are committed to the development of democracy," Tung said.
"Our political process will evolve in accordance with the Basic
Law. I believe this is in the best long-term interest of Hong
Kong."
</P>
<P>
Tung also told Cook that Hong Kong had put an end to the Port
of First Asylum policy for Vietnamese people arriving in Hong Kong
illegally in future and appealed to the British government to
accept more Vietnamese refugees and lobby other resettlement
countries to do the same.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that he was pleased to note an improved Sino-British
relationship and added that a mutually beneficial partnership
between China and Britain is good for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing Wednesday afternoon, Cook told reporters
that facts have proved that the "one country, two systems"
principle had been successful in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that he was confident in Hong Kong despite the
financial turmoil in the region. He said that he believed Hong
Kong will weather the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The smooth transition of Hong Kong has offered an opportunity
for a fresh start of the relationship between Britain and China
and Hong Kong can become a bridge for Britain to China, Cook
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
