<HEADLINE> Artificial Reefs Created to Improve Marine Habitat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A ferrocement barge was sunk
Wednesday in the northwest sea of Hong Kong, marking the beginning
of an artificial reefs project launched by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture and Fisheries Department (AFD), which
implemented the natural conservation project, said the deployment
of artificial reefs is one of the ways to alleviate the adverse
impacts on local marine habitat caused by coastal development,
pollution and overfishing.
</P>
<P>
An AFD spokesman said Wednesday that this redundant vessel was
among the 10 boats to be deployed as artificial reefs to serve as
a habitat for marine life in the first stage of the project.
</P>
<P>
Artificial reefs are very effective in aggregating fish and
would enhance existing habitat and fisheries resources, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
The 10 vessels, including wooden fishing boats, steel and
ferrocement river barges, will be placed in the seas over the next
 three years. The AFD has secured 100 million HK dollars (about
12.8 million U.S. dollars) for the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
