<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop on African Conflict Resolution Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA (Tanzania), January 21 (Xinhua) -- An international
workshop on African conflict resolution opened here today, at
which experience will be exchanged among African leaders and
mediators in a bid to stem widespread conflict in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni called for the establishment
of a regional mechanism to prevent and resolve conflicts in
Africa in his keynote speech at the opening ceremony held at the
Arusha International Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
He said there must be a regional mechanism with consistent
principles if conflicts are to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
He attributed African conflicts to underdevelopment and called
for industrialization and the political empowerment of the
people.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the empowerment of the people must be
tailored to specific circumstances of a nation. "Empowerment must
be flexible," he added.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said there must be punishment in the process of
conflict resolution. "There must be hanging of some people, as
soon as possible," he added.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts in Africa could be traced back long ago but western
colonialism and the "ideological poisoning" and manipulation by
colonialists are blamed for most conflicts in modern times, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The three-day gathering is also expected to discuss the role
played by civil society and African women in conflict resolution,
and institutional arrangements for conflict prevention,
management and resolution in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa, former Tanzanian president
Julius Nyerere and Tanzanian Foreign Minister Jakayna Kikwete
were present at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The forum, sponsored by the United Nations Development
Program, was jointly organized by the Tanzanian Foreign Ministry
and the Mwalimu Nyerere Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The workshop attracted some 200 African leaders,
peace-brokers, representatives from governments and international
organizations, and scholars from some 50 countries and more than
20 institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
