<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Military, Muslim Rebels Clash Anew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' rebel Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) on Wednesday accused the
government troops of shelling again their positions in a southern
Philippine town Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military affairs, was
quoted by a local television as saying the military bombardment
started around 1:00 a.m. Tuesday and stopped some three hours
later.
</P>
<P>
Murad said the military unleashed 50 rounds of 81 mm mortar
projectiles and some 10 rounds of 105 howitzer cannon shells on
the MILF defense lines near Buldon town in Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
But he said nobody was hurt on the rebel side, adding that MILF
forces retaliated with several mortar fires on military positions
in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Army's Sixth Infantry Division, whose troops are deployed
in Buldon, has not yet answered the MILF's accusations.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a series of renewed clashes erupted between the MILF
and the government troops near Buldon, killing one government
militiaman and four MILF rebels after an exchange of projectiles.
</P>
<P>
The latest rash of violence, which occurred after the signing
of a general ceasefire agreement last December by the two sides,
will probably affect the next round of peace talks in February.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled peace talks are expected to discuss the
possibility of and the agenda for reaching a preliminary peace
agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The MILF refused to be included in the peace treaty signed last
year by the government and the Moro National Liberation Front
(MNLF), and began its own peace talks with Manila in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated 12,000 members, the MILF is currently the
largest anti-government force in the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
