<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improves Partnership Between Reserves, Communities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The idea of balancing community development and nature
protection, which we call co-management, can be traced back
several decades, but so far it is still in a pilot stage in
China," said Scott McCormick, senior consultant working for the
GEF-China project.
</P>
<P>
According to McCormick, who has worked in many parts of the
world with co-management, "very positive channels have been
established to communicate with villagers, and all the eight
demonstration villages now have the potential to be very
successful."
</P>
<P>
In Foping National Nature Reserve in northwest China's Shaanxi
province, the reserve helped local villagers last year introduce
better bee varieties and improve edible fungus-growing
techniques. In neighboring Zhouzhi National Nature Reserve, an
agreement has been reached between the reserve and a surrounding
village to reduce the cutting of firewood in exchange for
assistance with community projects.
</P>
<P>
"Now the villagers are all eager to do something for the
reserve," said Zhang Jian, director of the Foping reserve
administration.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, most of the reserve's work was only to prevent
local villagers from illegal cutting and hunting, but now I have
begun to recognize that the way to do my job better is not to
conflict with the villagers, but to help them."
</P>
<P>
The consciousness of co-management is also becoming a common
concern in the Shennongjia National Nature Reserve in central
China's Hubei Province. Zhang Quan Yi, the reserve's
administration chief, said during an exclusive interview with
Xinhua that "good nature conservation can be only achieved when
good community development is achieved."
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Forestry, a countrywide drive to
improve relations between reserves and local communities will
begin soon after the year 2000 when initial experiences are drawn
from the GEF-China project.
</P>
<P>
"This will give the nation's nature conservation cause a real
good starting point," an official with the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Draws up 1998 Economic Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Beijing authorities today
announced plans to undertake some giant Sino-overseas joint
ventures while speeding up industrial readjustment in 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, sectors such as retail sales, finance,
insurance, tourism and cultural services will continue to
gradually open up to the outside world, said Yuan Zhenyu, director
of Beijing Planning Commission, at the first session of Beijing's
11th Municipal People's Congress which ended today.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the meeting approved the 1998 economic and
social development plan.
</P>
<P>
Support will be given to the development of large-scale
integrated circuits, third-phase expansion project of the
Beijing-Mitsushita Color CRT., the Sino-U.S. Jeep Corp., technical
upgrading project of the Dongfang Chemical Plant, the 2160-mm
hot-rolling mill project of the Capital Iron and Steel Group, Yuan
said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing people may see the merger this year of the Yanshan
Petrochemical Co. and the Dongfang Chemical Plant, and electronic
parts and power generating equipment groups will be established.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to further develop the Capital Iron and
Steel Group, Legend Group and Stone Group, etc., he said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's gross domestic product is expected to reach 200.8
billion yuan (24.2 billion U.S. dollars) this year, up 9 percent
allowing for inflation, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
The city expects to export 2.5 billion U.S. dollars worth of
goods and use a total of 1.8 billion U.S. dollars of overseas
funds.
</P>
<P>
Income of rural people and urban residents is expected to grow
by 3 to 5 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the city will keep the unemployment
rate below 1 percent. Some 60 percent of the laid-off workers will
be given job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Another eight million square meters of residential buildings
also will be completed this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
