<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Group Raises 4.9 Million Yuan for Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The China Charity Federation
(CCF) announced here today that over the past week and more, it
has raised 4.9 million yuan (about 600,000 US dollars) in donation
for the quake-stricken area in Zhangjiakou of Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiakou, a major city in northern Hebei, was hit by an
earthquake measured 6.2 on the Richter scale on January 10. The
tremor killed 50 people, injured more than 10,000, and damaged
over 100,000 houses.
</P>
<P>
Yan Mingfu, vice president of CCF, said that the federation
began to receive social donations on the first work day after the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
"Within one week, we received donations worth one and a half
million yuan, as well as nearly 2,000 clothes from Beijing
residents," he said, adding that all the donations had been sent
to the quake-afflicted areas on January 13, 16 and 19.
</P>
<P>
Starting on January 19, he said, the CCF started a new round of
fund-raising to help the reconstruction in the quake-stricken
areas, especially the rebuilding of schools, old folks' homes and
local people's houses.
</P>
<P>
"To date, we have received two million yuan from the
headquarters of Bank of Communications, Guangzhou Jockeys' Club
and a charity fund based in Hong Kong," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, 50 noted TV hosts and performers, who are now busy
rehearsing on a soiree to be broadcast live on China Central
Television on the eve of the Chinese lunar new year, informed the
CCF by phone that they would each donate a makeshift house to
students in quake-afflicted areas as temporary classrooms. The
houses are estimatedly worth nearly 400,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
CCF offices across the country also received donations worth a
total of one million yuan, Yan added.
</P>
<P>
He conceded that due to the bitter cold that has frozen the
surface of earth, it would not be possible for the reconstruction
work to start until May.
</P>
<P>
"But I promise that the CCF will try its best to make full and
proper use of every penny of the donations," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
