<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improves Partnership Between Reserves, Communities (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese nature conservation
staff members are beginning to doubt the traditional philosophy of
keeping people away from wild areas.
</P>
<P>
They are trying to establish a partnership between the nation's
nearly 800 nature reserves and their surrounding villages to seek
more cooperation and participation.
</P>
<P>
In Xiahuibian, a remote Hani ethnic group village bordering the
Xishuangbanna National Nature Reserve in southwest China's Yunnan
Province, villagers recently received a group of nature reserve
staff members with a grand feast.
</P>
<P>
"We are negotiating with the villagers for better cooperation
by investing in a hydro-power station and helping to improve the
villagers' farming methods and incomes," said Cai Jialin from the
reserve administration.
</P>
<P>
According to Yin Hong, deputy section chief in charge of the
nature reserve management with the Ministry of Forestry,
Xiahuibian is now one of eight pilot villages in China.
</P>
<P>
Starting two years ago, Yin said, the Ministry of Forestry and
the Global Environment Facility (GEF) launched a project to
improve China's nature conservation and especially encourage more
involvement of local communities in conservation. The project will
last six years and cost 23.6 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
