<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popov Wins 100 Meter Freestyle at World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, Janurary 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian world champion Alex
Popov kept his 100 meter freestyle record intact when he won the
short-course title at World Cup swim meet in Sydney on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a rematch of their Perth world championship final, Popov was
again too fast for Australia's Michael Klim with a time of 47.46
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Klim, who won seven medals at the Perth worlds including four
gold, finished second in 47.69.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 50 meter breaststroke, German Mark Warnecke
finished first ahead of New Zealand's Paul Kent.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 400 meter freestyle, Italian Emiliano Brembilla
won in 3:41.93 and teammate Massimilia Rosolino was third. World
400-meter champion Ian Thorpe of Australia was second.
</P>
<P>
Russian Andrei Korneev won the men's 200 meter breaststroke,
Yana Klochkova of Ukraine the 200 meter individual medley in
2:12.36 and German Katrin Meissner the 50 meter freestyle.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100 meter individual medley, American Ron Karnaugh
was first ahead of Britain's James Hickman and Josh Davis of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Antje Buschschulte of Germany won the women's 50 meter
backstroke from Australian pair Giaan Rooney and Dyana Calub and
later picked up her second win when she claimed the 200 meter
backstroke title.
</P>
<P>
Dual world gold medalist Chen Yan of China won the women's 200
meter freestyle in 1:56.57.
</P>
<P>
Australian Samantha Riley easily won the 100 meter breaststroke
in 1:06.72, beating Brigitte Becue of Belgium and Svetlana
Bondarenko of Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands took the top two spots in the women's 800 meter
freestyle with Kirsten Vlieghuis finishing in 8:21.94 ahead of
Carla Geurts and Australian Rachel Harris. 
</P>
