<HEADLINE> Williams Wins Family Duel at Australian Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Open finalist Venus
Williams won the much-expected family duel with her younger sister
serena at the Australian Open on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bigger sister Venus struggled through the first set 7-6 before
sealing the second set victory 6-1 in a more comfortable way.
</P>
<P>
Men's seeds kept falling in Melbourne as Spaniard Carlos Moya,
last year's runner-up, became the latest highly ranked victim
after his 4-6, 6-4, 7-6 (7-2), 6-4 loss to unseeded Richard
Fromberg of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Before this match, local hopeful Mark Philippoussis lost a
thrilling five-set clash against Moroccan lefthander Hicham Arazi,
leaving just 10 of the 16 seeds standing after three days' play at
Melbourne Park.
</P>
<P>
The world number 15 Australian crashed out 1-6, 6-2, 4-6, 6-1,
9-7 after an exhausting three hours encounter.
</P>
<P>
Men's fourth seed Jonas Bjorkman saved himself from becoming
another seed victim as he lost the first two sets against his
South African nemesis Wayne Ferreira before fighting back to win
6-7, 4-6, 6-4, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seeded Czech Petr Korda made no mistake with another
unseeded Australian Scott Draper, beating him 7-6, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
In other ties, Spain's 11th seed Alex Corretja beat German
David Prinosil 6-4, 6-3, 6-0 and Belarussian Natasha Zvereva
downed Italy's Rita Grande 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Women's second seed Lindsay Davenport flirted with danger
against Slovakia's Karina Habsudova as she scored a hard-earned
2-6, 6-0, 9-7. 
</P>
