<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outlook Stable for Australian Wool: Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The long-term outlook for
Australian wool sales remained generally stable despite the Asian
currency crisis, the Wool Council of Australia (WCA) said
Wednesday in its latest analysis.
</P>
<P>
"While there has been a fall-off in demand and a price
deterioration in recent weeks, we are hopeful this is short term,
driven principally by currency instability and uncertainty in
Asia," WCA Executive Director Greg Evans said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The council analysis ... suggests in the longer term the
fundamentals remain sound with reasonable gross domestic product
(GDP) growth in our key markets and a modest production outlook
providing a platform for improving prices."
</P>
<P>
Evans conceded that the crisis has an impact on specific
markets and has given buyers a reason to temporarily retreat from
the market.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that it is important for the wool industry to
maintain a proper perspective on the extent of the Asian financial
meltdown and its probable impact on the industry's fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
South Korea only took about 6 percent of Australia's wool
exports in the fiscal year of 1996-1997, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the turmoil, other key markets including China, Europe
and the Americas appear to be remaining firm," he said.
</P>
<P>
Evans said conditions over the next six to 12 months would
largely be dictated by the ongoing stability of the Chinese
market, Japan's ability to meet its 1998 GDP growth forecast and
European demand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
