<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taylor Denies Asking for ECOMOG's Withdrawal From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor has denied that he is demanding the west African
peace-keeping force ECOMOG to leave his country by February 2,
saying that what he wants is the change of their mission and
mandate.
</P>
<P>
"The February 2 deadline is not for the withdrawal of ECOMOG
forces from Liberia. February 2 is for the technical change of
the mandate. What we are asking is that their mission and its
mandate must change on February 2," Taylor told the Voice of
America on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He accused some people in the ECOMOG of trying to exercise the
same control over Liberia as they did before the election and
made it clear that he did not want anyone to share his power as
the president.
</P>
<P>
"There is no parallel government in Liberia. Whatever unit
would be here would work with the president and the government of
the Republic of Liberia," Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG, a sub-regional force under the command of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), has been in Liberia
since 1990 when the Liberia civil war broke out.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, who emerged the winner of the successful presidential
election monitored by ECOMOG, had agreed with ECOWAS that the
ECOMOG will stay in Liberia until August to help rebuild its
national army.
</P>
<P>
He, however, seemed to have changed his mind later, accusing
the ECOMOG of trying to be an independent power center and
demanded its total pullout by February 2.
</P>
<P>
There are speculations that he had urged the United States to
train the national army for Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Preparing for a final pullout, Nigeria, the main contributor
of troops to the ECOMOG, had already called back 1,205 soldiers
last month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi has been busy
with consultations with west African leaders over the fate of the
ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Acting on the mandate of the ECOWAS Chairman and Nigerian Head
of State, General Sani Abacha, Ikimi had visited Ghana, Togo,
Guinea and Liberia last week and is expected to visit more ECOWAS
member states this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
