<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Rejects Iraqi Proposal on Arms Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief arms inspector
Richard Butler has rejected an Iraqi proposal to freeze the
inspectors' access to presidential and sovereign sites, at least
for now.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz, Butler said Iraq has proposed to freeze
U.N. arms inspectors' access to the sites until technical
evaluation meetings come to an end in April.
</P>
<P>
He said he had told the Iraqis that he "can not or will not"
agree to this proposal until he received different instructions
from the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Tariq Aziz proposed that we should freeze any further
discussions or actions with respect to the issue of inspecting
presidential and sovereign sites until the results of those
technical evaluation meetings come out," Butler said.
</P>
<P>
"He (Aziz) said if when those meetings are finished, and I have
the positive results that he foresees, the only obstacle to the
lifting of the embargo was this question of access to
presidential and sovereign sites, then he and I should meet again
in April to talk about it," he told the press conference.
</P>
<P>
Butler said Aziz ruled out the possibility that Iraq would
provide any new information.
</P>
<P>
"He (Aziz) said that all of the information as to Iraq's
disposal is known to us, it would be compiled in specific forms
suitable for each of those meetings, but he did not expect there
will be any new information," said Butler.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said technical evaluation meetings would
begin on the first of February in Baghdad, one meeting on missile
warheads, another on chemical weapons, in particular on the
chemical "VX", and a few weeks after that, a meeting will begin on
the whole biological file.
</P>
<P>
Butler said the aim of establishing those meetings is to solve
differences between UNSCOM and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Those meetings will be participated by international experts
from five permanent member states of the Security Council and
Germany in addition to experts from Iraq and UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said he expressed his "very serious doubt that
the terms of technical evaluation meetings could have the outcome
that he (Aziz) foresaw."
</P>
<P>
Butler said the (Security) Council's instruction to him as of
today was for him to continue full work of this commission in
pursuit of its mandate.
</P>
<P>
He said he could not rule out the possibility that he would
authorize U.N. arms inspectors to go to a place in one of these
presidential and sovereign sites.
</P>
<P>
"I can not rule out that tomorrow, the next day, whenever, my
professionals might put to me a proposal which is justified by
evidence available to us, they would have me authorize the
inspection to go to a place of one of these presidential and
sovereign sites," Butler said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that "if that is the case, I would do it,
unless the Council instructs me otherwise."
</P>
<P>
Butler said he had come to Baghdad as the Council's
representative with a very specific brief, a brief to "get Iraq to
come back into compliance to accept its obligation to allow us to
go anywhere in the country without conditions, without hindrance,
to carry out our work."
</P>
<P>
He said that he could not predict what the Council would make
of that.
</P>
<P>
Butler said the Iraqi side had identified eight presidential
sites throughout the country, but said he did not know the number
of buildings in them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Mayor Re-elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Jia Qinglin was re-elected
mayor on the final day of the first session of the 11th Beijing
Municipal People's Congress today.
</P>
<P>
The 57-year-old mayor is also the secretary of the Beijing
Municipal Committee of the Chinese Communist Party. He is among
the top city and provincial officials who hold both the top posts
of party and government concurrently.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, eight deputy mayors were elected, four of
whom are new.
</P>
<P>
Jin Renqin, Meng Xuenong, Lin Wenyi and Yue Fuhong remained as
deputy mayors. Wang Huangtao, Liu Haiyan, Liu Jingmin and Zhang
Mao were elected deputy mayors for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The average age of Beijing's top officials is 51; six of them
are post-graduates and the rest have received university
educations.
</P>
<P>
Lin Wenyi, the only woman deputy mayor, had been a tutor for
doctoral degree candidates at Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Wang Guangtao, 55, has a post-graduate degree in urban
construction. The Shanghai native was mayor of Harbin before he
was elected today as Beijing's deputy mayor.
</P>
<P>
Liu Haiyan, chairman of the Beijing Yanshan Petrochemical
Group, has rich experience in managing large state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jinmin had been working in the city's urban construction
department for many years.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Mao, 43, is the youngest of the deputy mayors. He had
been deputy head of the Municipal Commission of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation and head of Beijing's New Technology
Development Zone.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the new deputy mayors have been
chosen to deal with such pressing city problems as urban
construction, management of state-owned enterprises and
development of high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jianmin was re-elected as chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Beijing Municipal People's Congress at today's
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
