<HEADLINE> S. Korea Develops Fiber System Over Cellular Phone Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 21 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's LG Telecom has
developed a fiber system that will improve call quality of a
mobile phone network and cut the cost of network construction, the
local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The new system uses fiber optic cable networks and small
transceiver units, called remote radio frequency (RF) heads, to
connect with a cellular phone communication hub.
</P>
<P>
These RF heads receive optical signals from a communications
service hub into another's air frequencies for transmission to
subscribers' handsets.
</P>
<P>
Equipped with antennae, the heads can also receive calls from
subscribers and convert them into optical signals for transmission
to a communication hub, which then delivers the calls to their
destinations through telephone networks.
</P>
<P>
The main advantage of the fiber system is that installation of
the small RF heads and their antennae is very easy and flexible.
</P>
<P>
The installation of the RF units doesn't require those high
steel towers needed to deploy base transceiver systems. They can
be installed on electrical poles, buildings or other structures.
</P>
<P>
This means that the time and costs to build PCS networks can be
reduced significantly.
</P>
<P>
The new system also improves call quality since it can be
located closer to subscribers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
