<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Improves Literacy Among Young </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The literacy rate of the young
and middle-aged in East China's Anhui Province was raised from
80.5 percent in 1990 to 96.25 percent this year thanks to the
government effort to wipe out illiteracy, according to local
sources.
</P>
<P>
One concrete measure the local government took was to provide
courses to spread basic knowledge among more than 600,000
illiterates and semi-illiterates in the province, 69 percent of
whom have passed the exams.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 25,000 classes covering practical skills
of agriculture were held in the province last year; 1,015,000
farmers attended these classes, and 5,940,000 rural people went to
county- or village-level training classes.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial education committee, Anhui is
expected to raise the literacy rate of the young to more than 97
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
China has recorded great progress in eliminating illiteracy,
with some 60 million Chinese people, including 25 youngsters and 35
million adults.
</P>
<P>
However, some 145 million Chinese people are still illiterate,
37.5 million of whom are youngsters, or approximately 25 percent of
the total. Females living in poverty-stricken and mountainous
areas account for the vast majority of the illiterate
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
