<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Strives for Good Environment for Trade: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Trade Department
made continued efforts in 1997 to ensure that Hong Kong has the
best possible external and internal environment for trade,
Director General of Trade Alan Lai said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Externally our main objective is to promote liberalization of
international trade through efforts at the multilateral, regional
and bilateral levels, and internally, we made further steps in
ensuring that our trade regulation systems achieve their purposes
in ways that are most facilitating and business-friendly," Lai
told a media session.
</P>
<P>
The main fora at the multilateral and regional levels are
respectively the World Trade Organization (WTO) and Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC).
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, as a separate customs territory and a separate
member of the WTO, continued to participate actively in the work
of the WTO during the year, Lai noted.
</P>
<P>
The successful conclusion of the negotiations on basic
telecommunications and financial services and the conclusion of an
agreement on information technology during the year in the WTO
were very beneficial to Hong Kong's export of services and goods,
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The commemoration of the 50th anniversary of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), the predecessor of the WTO,
will be held in May this year to pay tribute to the achievements
of the multilateral trading system. The second WTO Ministerial
Conference will be held prior to the anniversary celebrations.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will pursue the idea of launching a new round of
broad-based multilateral negotiations by the turn of the century
actively in the WTO with a view to achieving our ultimate goal of
global free trade and investment," the trade official said.
</P>
<P>
On the regional level, 1997 was the first year that the Special
Administrative Region participated in the APEC Economic Leaders
Meeting and Ministerial Meeting under the name of "Hong Kong,
China". "Hong Kong remains a separate and full member of APEC in
its own right," Lai said.
</P>
<P>
In Vancouver, Canada, APEC member economies agreed to pursue
early voluntary trade liberalization in 15 sectors, with nine
sectors under fast track action.
</P>
<P>
"We are particularly encouraged to see our toys proposal
selected as one of the nine fast track items. It is estimated that
about 1.5 billion HK dollars (192 million U.S. dollars) of Hong
Kong's domestic export of toys will benefit," Lai said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
