<HEADLINE> Iran Releases 2 Sudanese POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran has released two Sudanese
prisoners of war (POW) captured during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq war,
local daily Jomhuri Eslami reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that the two Sudanese were sent to the Sudanese
Embassy in Tehran Sunday according to an agreement reached between
the two countries on the sidelines of the eighth Islamic summit
held here last December.
</P>
<P>
The report did not identify the freed Sudanese, nor did it give
any further details. But it said they were sent by former Sudanese
government to join the Iraqi army fighting Iran.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's envoy here thanked Iran for the "humanitarian measure"
and expressed regret that the Sudanese were involved in the
Iran-Iraq bloodshed, the daily added.
</P>
<P>
Iran had released last month two Jordanian POWs following
talks between Iranian and Jordanian officials at the Islamic
summit.
</P>
<P>
During the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, many Arab mercenaries
joined the Iraqi army to fight Iran, a non-Arab country in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Iran released most of the Arab POWs in 1991. It was reported
that Tehran is still keeping several hundreds of POWs, most of
them Iraqis. 
</P>
