<HEADLINE> S'pore Manufacturing Output Increases in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's manufacturing
output rose by 10.3 percent year-on-year in November 1997, with
the cumulative output for the first 11 months of the year jumping
by 4 percent over a year earlier, the Economic Development Board
(EDB) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the increase in November was broad-based with
growth recorded in the electronics, chemicals and engineering
clusters.
</P>
<P>
The electronics cluster grew by 10.3 percent in November
compared with a year ago. Growth in semiconductors, computer
peripherals and printed circuit boards assembled (PCBAs) bolstered
the industry.
</P>
<P>
However, the EDB said growth in disk drives was not as vigorous
as before because of over-capacity worldwide while the output of
telecommunication equipment, personal computers and consumer
electronics declined.
</P>
<P>
Electronics output for the first 11 months of 1997 rose by 2.9
percent over the same months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
As for the chemicals cluster, the cumulative output for the
period between January and November was 14.4 percent higher than
the corresponding period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The output of petrochemical products soared by 121.3 percent in
November, it said, adding that while new plants increased their
production, output from some existing plants was disrupted due to
short maintenance shutdowns in the month.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative output of the 11 months went up by a hefty 81.2
percent over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The output of the pharmaceuticals sub-cluster decreased by 22.3
percent year-on-year due to less export orders from Europe.
Cumulative output for the first 11 months of the year was 1.8
percent lower than the same period of 1996, the EDB said.
</P>
</TEXT>
