<HEADLINE> China Reports Increased Policy Loans to Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import Bank of China
(EximBank) has reported growth in policy loans for Chinese
exporters of capital goods like machinery and electronics products
for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The bank loaned 17.62 billion yuan (about 2.1 billion US
dollars) and 75.91 million US dollars last year, up 37 percent and
85 percent from 1996. Credit for buyers of exports amounted to
81.75 million US dollars, more than eight times the 1996 figure,
and there was growth in export credit insurance and guarantee
business, amounting to 350 million US dollars and 622 million US
dollars worth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The EximBank also rolled over 2.6 billion US dollars in
overseas government loans last year and approved 670 million US
dollars in low-interest loans to foreign nations.
</P>
<P>
As a national policy bank for financing capital goods exports
of machinery products and other equipment, EximBank has lent great
support to Chinese exporters with export credits, export credit
insurance, and guarantees since it was established in 1994. It has
approved more than 40 billion yuan and 224 million US dollars in
export credits, helping give Chinese machinery exporters 1.15
billion US dollars in earnings. 
</P>
