<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Commercial banks will become real banks with autonomy in
business decisions and a modern banking system established with
boards of directors and internal control systems.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with international loan practices, China will
develop a new loan classification system to improve commercial
banks' loans.
</P>
<P>
Although the SE Asian financial crisis does not seem to pose a
direct threat to China, the hidden dangers that led to the crisis
also exist to some degree in China's financial sector, and the
central bank has taken heed and decided to further increase
financial controls.
</P>
<P>
Central bank sources say that illegal financial institutions
will be stopped, and the banking, trust, securities and insurance
sectors separated, and financial institutions will have to
increase self discipline to improve order by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
To balance supply and demand, China will continue to try to
avoid a bubble economy in real estate and securities and to
maintain a rational structure in foreign debt, monetary system,
and exchange rate. The convertibility of the renminbi will come
gradually and conditionally.
</P>
<P>
The reforms of the past few years have provided good conditions
for the financial sector reaching its three-year reform
goals. Since 1994, the financial sector has developed steadily, at
a time when many Asian countries have been dragged into financial
crises and are suffering heavily. China's financial system is
still healthy, demonstrating China's ability to avoid economic and
financial risks.
</P>
<P>
China is now pushing its financial reform to higher levels, a
move that is needed by a socialist market economy and one that is
a realistic way of coping with the new international economic
conditions, and the central bank says it is confident that the
reform measures will achieve the desired results.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
