<HEADLINE> Guangdong's Foreign Trade Tops 130 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 21 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province reported robust growth in its foreign trade last year,
with total exports and imports valued at more than 130 billion US
dollars for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade volume of Guangdong was about 40 percent of
the national total.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show that Guangdong's exports surged 24
percent to 74.56 billion US dollars last year, while its imports
rose 10 percent to 55.56 billion US dollars. The trade surplus of
19.9 billion US dollars was 1.2 times more than that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that Guangdong reported a 15 percent increase
in its processing trade, which accounted for 70 percent of the
Chinese province's total foreign trade volume last year.
</P>
<P>
Also last year Guangdong's general trade soared 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the figures have combined to indicate that
Guangdong has basically countered the negative effects brought by
reductions in the export rebate rates and has successfully
improved its ability to ward off risks related to foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, exports and imports of Guangdong's
state-owned foreign trade enterprises rose 24 percent in 1997, 9.4
percentage points higher than that of overseas-funded
enterprises. 
</P>
