<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Sees Moderate Export Performance in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's total exports are
projected to have grown by around 4 percent in value terms to
1,453 billion HK dollars (186.3 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997,
Trade Department statistics showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After netting out a small decline in export prices, the growth
rate in real terms was about 6 percent, higher than the 5 percent
increase recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Trade Alan Lai noted that export
performance remained moderate in 1997, dampened largely by price
and demand factors.
</P>
<P>
The sustained strength of the U.S. dollar, and hence Hong Kong
dollar, weakened the price competitiveness of Hong Kong products
in overseas markets while import demand in Japan and Britain was
generally slack.
</P>
<P>
But Lai pointed out that exports to China's inland areas and
the United States, the two biggest trading partners of Hong Kong,
showed sustained growth in 1997, underpinned by the generally
robust performance in these two economies.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the substantial currency depreciation in
some East Asian economies since the middle of 1997 did not
materially affected Hong Kong's overall export performance in the
latter half of 1997 as their combined share in Hong Kong's total
exports was relatively small.
</P>
<P>
Within total exports, domestic exports are estimated to have
declined by about 1 percent in value terms to 211 billion HK
dollars (27.1 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997. After discounting a
small decrease in prices, the growth in real terms was about 2
percent, in contrast to the 8 percent decline in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports are estimated to have increased by about 5 percent
in value terms to 1,242 billion HK dollars (159.2 billion U.S.
dollars). The growth rate in real terms was about 7 percent,
slightly slower than the 8 percent increase in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Total trade in goods is estimated to have grown by around 5
percent in value terms to 3,073 billion HK dollars (394 billion
U.S. dollars) in 1997. After netting out price changes, there was
an increase of about 6 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong was placed seventh in world trade in 1996 by the
World Trade Organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Residents Make Donations for Quake-Hit Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Macao residents are enthusiastic
about making donations to the earthquake-hit Hebei Province in
northern China despite a sluggish economic performance in the
territory over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Many representatives of the local business community and
companies came to the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch to hand over
the donations over the past few days. The total sum of donations
Xinhua received had reached 3.41 million Hong Kong dollars (about
440,560 U.S. dollars) by Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The largest single donation came from the Macao Development
Promotion Association, which is mainly composed of real estate
business people. Their contributions added up to 1,369,250 patacas
 (about 171,156 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Apart from companies and communities, individual residents also
came to Xinhua to make donations. They included one elderly who
asked not to be identified but contributed 500,000 Hong Kong
dollars (about 64,600 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, charity groups and the Macao Red Cross also
publicized their special bank accounts for donations.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua staff in Macao donated a total of 126,300 Hong Kong
dollars (about 16,300 U.S. dollars) themselves.
</P>
<P>
Zong Guangyao, deputy director of the Xinhua Macao Branch, said
many Macao residents called Xinhua to ask about the earthquake
after it happened on January 10. He praised Macao residents'
enthusiasm despite an economic slowdown in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake that rocked Zhangbei and Shangyi counties killed
more than 50 people and injured more than 10,000 others. Tens of
thousands of people were left homeless in the biting cold of minus
30 degrees Celsius.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
