<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British FM Optimistic About One Country, Two Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The first six months after
Hong Kong returned to China make people optimistic that "one
country, two systems" has been transformed from an imaginative
concept to a concrete reality, visiting British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon organized by the British Chamber of
Commerce in Hong and Asia House in his honor, Cook said that the
first six months after the handover have provided welcome evidence
that the Chinese government is able and willing to give Hong Kong
the autonomy promised in the Basic Law, and to let Hong Kong
people govern Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
They are six months that have shown the government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) continuing to run Hong
Kong fairly and efficiently, to the benefit of the people of Hong
Kong, said Cook, who arrived in Hong Kong Tuesday following his
visit to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They are six months that have shown the rule of law is alive
and well, along with the impartiality and excellence of the Hong
Kong civil service, Cook added.
</P>
<P>
"So far, in spite of the new economic challenges, our
confidence in the future of Hong Kong has been reinforced," the
foreign secretary said.
</P>
<P>
The business relationship between Britain and Hong Kong
continues to grow, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Britain is the largest foreign investor in Hong Kong and many
British companies have decided to use Hong Kong as a base for
their activities in China and the rest of Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the other direction, Britain already receives 80 percent of
all Hong Kong's investment in Europe, investment in the production
of everything from silicon chips in South Wales to compact discs
in Belfast, he added.
</P>
<P>
After the handover, Hong Kong can become a bridge for Britain
to China.
</P>
<P>
The new government in Britain and the success of the handover
here has given both Britain and China a chance for a fresh start
of the relationship between Britain and China, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"Our relations with China have entered a new phase, and are
strengthening across the board," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
This is in the interests of everyone, the British and the
Chinese, including the people of Hong Kong, he added.
</P>
<P>
China has a key place in the world, and there is huge scope for
Britain and China to work together, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"I do not need to tell anyone here about the attractions of
doing business in China. British companies have seen the
opportunities, and are by far the largest European investors,"
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"But above all, what we are aiming to do is develop a closer
relationship that recognizes the global importance of China's
remarkable recent progress," he added.
</P>
<P>
China is not just a market, it is one of the global powers of
the 21st century, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook paid a visit to Beijing On January 19-20, during which he
met with Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
