<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana's Nominal Interest Rate Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Botswana's nominal
interest rate declined in 1997 while the real prime rate went up,
the Bank of Botswana (BOB) said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The three month BOB certificates, which were pegged at 12.22
percent at the end of 1996, lost 0.82 points to 11.40 percent by
December 31,1997.
</P>
<P>
The BOB's decline phase started at the beginning of August
last year and was sustained until the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Comparatively, the rate put on 0.26 points over 1996.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the rate has dropped a further 0.63 points
to 10.77 percent. The bank rate dropped half a point over 1997 to
12.5 percent. It has subsequently dropped another half a point to
12 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the bank rate hovered around 13 percent. At the last
reported date, September 30, prime was at 14 percent, having
dropped half a point from the 1996 close of 14.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Real prime rate was reported at 5.1 percent on September 30,
up 0.6 points from 4.5 percent on December 31, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
