<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Underground Water Found in Desert in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Remarkable successes have been
reported in seeking for underground water in northwest China's
Tarim Basin, Gansu Corridor and Loess Highlands.
</P>
<P>
The finds will greatly help relieve water shortage in the
areas, according to an official with the Ministry of Geology and
Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China is rich in natural resources and has great
potential for development. However, economic development of the
areas has been restricted by the shortage of water. In 1996, the
Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources initiated a plan of
looking for water in northwest China in order to boost local
economic development and improve local people's livelihood.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, potable underground water was discovered in the inner
area of Tarim Basin, which had been known as the "sea of
death". In Xitong township, Yieshi city in Gansu, a well with a
capacity of 720 cubic meters per day has been dug, offering
drinking water for more than 6,000 local residents.
</P>
<P>
Wells with high quality water have also been dug in Shaanxi
Province. And freshwater has been found in Ejin Plain in the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region, benefiting 10,000 local residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
