<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Leaves Heavy Tolls in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Freetown, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people who fled
the fighting in Tongo Fields in the east of Sierra Leone over the
weekend to Kenema Tuesday spoke of seeing dozens of headless
corpses along the 35 mile route.
</P>
<P>
"Many of the corpses were males between the ages of 18 and 20
and some wore without shoes or clothes, said a middle aged man in
a telephone interview in Kenema.
</P>
<P>
A woman said, "It is difficult to express just what I saw. It
was as if they were just rags discarded for dumper trucks to
collect them."
</P>
<P>
She explained that many of the corpses were bound by hide
ropes and naked.
</P>
<P>
A lorry driver who was one of the last civilians to flee Tongo
Field before government troops recaptured Tongo Field Sunday
night said the area has been completely devastated by stray
shells and rockets.
</P>
<P>
Health officials in Kenema said they were worried over a
possible epidemic outbreak because of the abandoned corpses, many
of which are lodged in thick bushes.
</P>
<P>
"We don't have vehicles and even if we do, we will be faced
with the shortage of fuel, " a health officer added.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone Red Cross personnel in Kenema said the Food they
now have will run out within the next two weeks and they would be
forced to undertake humanitarian crossborder operations to bring
food in from the stock in neighboring Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities said they are puzzled as to who or what
group is responsible for the corpses.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the fighting between soldiers and the Kamajors
have become nasty as both sides are disregarding some of the
basic elements of treating prisoners of war.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
