<HEADLINE> Macao Announces Progress in Civil Service Localization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The announcement, made by the Government Information Office,
said that 500 positions of the leadership have been localized by
January 15 as the Government put the localization of civil service
and training as a top priority.
</P>
<P>
The highest degree of localization has been achieved at the
section chief level, which reached 98.1 percent. The next is head
of group, which reached 90.6 percent, and head of division, 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
Macao civil service's highest rank is director of department,
followed by chief of division, chief of section, head of group and
head of sub-group. An undersecretary of the governor takes charge
of several departments.
</P>
<P>
There were also several local residents appointed as deputy
directors of departments and one as director.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Rangel, undersecretary for Civil Administration,
Education and Youth Affairs, was quoted as saying that the
ongoing localization work is expected to have evident progress in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira said in the middle of 1997
that all Portuguese civil servants hired in Macao will be phased
out and the civil service forces will be basically localized by
the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Some departments are making new appointments now, and the
next target of localization will be the directors and deputy
directors of departments," Rangel said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
