<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe: Land Reform to Go Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will not accept
perpetual occupation of most of its fertile land by white
commercial farmers and will go ahead with its land reform to
ensure equality in land distribution, President Robert Mugabe
said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing hundreds of people at the Ellerton farm in Beatrice
near Harare, Mugabe lambasted the foreign media for giving
impression that the Zimbabwean Government wanted to abandon the
land acquisition program.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, he said, could never be an extension of Britain and
since the government was acting on the basis of principle, there
was no going back.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going back on the land issue. We cannot accept
perpetual occupation of most of our fertile land by a few white
commercial farmers," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As we take the farms, we are not saying that those capable
should go away. We simply do not want them to continue to have
the most fertile land than most of us. We want equal
distribution," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government recently released a list of 1480
commercial farms for compulsory acquisition and decided to
redistribute these farms to landless families in its efforts to
accelerate the land resettlement program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
