<HEADLINE> Namibia to Ban Importation of Nuclear Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian Environment
and Tourism Ministry will table in parliament a law banning the
importation of poisonous and nuclear waste in the country,
according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The environmental management act is being drafted and would
"give effect to the constitutional directive on the subject,"
Namibian Environment Minister Philemon Malima said today.
</P>
<P>
Malima was responding to a call by environmental group
Earthlife Africa for government to clarify its position on toxic
waste dumping.
</P>
<P>
Malima said it had always been Nambia's policy not to allow
the dumping, storage, recycling or incineration of foreign waste
in Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Earthlife Africa last week wrote the letter demanding
clarification on the government's policy after rumours surfaced
that a South African company was hoping to import New York city's
waste into Namibia or Mozambique for burning.
</P>
<P>
It also called on other African countries to follow Namibia's
example and ban the importation of toxic waste. 
</P>
</TEXT>
