<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Banks to Grant More Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Banks in the Shenzhen Special
Economic Zone plan to grant 23 billion yuan (2.771 billion US
dollars) in loans during 1998, a year-on-year rise of 22 percent,
according to a plan announced by the Shenzhen Branch of the
People's Bank of China, the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at yesterday's banking conference, Jiang Chaoliang,
director of the Shenzhen branch, called on commercial banks to
increase loans for fixed-asset investments by between 15-20
percent, and to guarantee outstanding loans for the city's key
projects, key state enterprises and high-tech development which
account for some 10 percent of total loans.
</P>
<P>
This year's financing focus will be on housing, and the city
has pledged to introduced regulations governing mortgage loans
during the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding Renminbi loans granted by local banks stood at
120.3 billion yuan at the end of 1997, up 17.5 percent on the
beginning of the year. In addition, outstanding foreign currency
loans ended 7.8 billion US dollars, up 9.2 percent, and the total
volume of loans from overseas financial institutions amounted to
4.59 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, interbank calls amongst local banks reached 83.2
billion yuan, a substantial rise of 46.4 percent, with financing
using interbank cashiers and commercial checks rising by 78
percent to 18.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange settlements hit 19 billion US dollars, up 29.2
percent. and transactions in renminbi and foreign exchange rose 10
percent to 6.6 billion US dollars, respective rises of 29.2
percent and 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
