<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Used To Protect Cultural Relics in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi
Province has attracted foreign funds to protect and further study
the cultural relics in the province.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that the province has 35,750 immovable
historical sites including 55 major historical and cultural sites
under state protection. More than 650,000 pieces of cultural
relics are housed in various museums, including 123 cited as
national treasure.
</P>
<P>
The mausoleum of Qinshihuang, the first emperor of the Qin
Dynasty (221-206 B.C.), at Lintong, Shaanxi, and terracotta
figurines of warriors and horses near the tomb found in 1974, have
been listed in World Heritage. The site of the ancient Chang'an
city of the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220 A.D.) and the forest of
steles in Xi'an are seeking to enter the World Heritage list.
</P>
<P>
For many years the central and local governments have made
efforts to attract foreign funds to protect the cultural
relics. So far, China has cooperated with foreign countries
including Italy, Germany and Japan in the field.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government has provided a total of 4.8 billion lira
(about four million US dollars) to build a cultural relics
protection and renovation center in Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
Germany has invested 600,000 mark (about 400,000 US dollars) to
renovate a Buddhist monastery in Binxian County. It has also
helped build a laboratory to repair terracotta warriors and horses.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi Archaeological Research Institute has enjoyed
cooperation with a German museum for seven years. Their German
counterparts have provided funding and advanced equipment
including detectors, computers and traffic facilities for
historical sites exploration and survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
