<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Bank Deregulates Currencies Except U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of Pakistan
(SBP) has granted a general permission to authorized currency
dealers to determine their own rates of exchange for various
currencies except the U.S. dollar, it was officially announced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank issued a circular to all authorized dealers in
foreign exchange on Wednesday stating that its Foreign Exchange
Rates Committee (FERC) will not publish the exchange rates of
various currencies other than the U.S. dollar to the Pakistan
rupee with effect from February 5, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The FERC, to date, has been fixing the rates of 25 currencies
including the U.S. dollar, British pound and Deutsche mark.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the greenback to the Pakistani rupee will
continue to be determined and published by the State Bank of
Pakistan, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
In view of the permission granted, the SBP decided to delink
the purchase of foreign exchange other than the U.S. dollar by
importers from the relative letter of credit/registered agreement,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The SBP's move is seen as a big step forward to suppress rumors
about the devaluation of the U.S. dollar and an effort to tackle
the fallout of the financial turmoil in Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
"It is a good omen that the government has taken measures to
ease the pressure of the dollar on the economy of Pakistan by
deregulating other currencies," a local banker pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistani exporters have virtually been brought at par
with international competitors particularly those in Europe and
Far East.
</P>
<P>
"The international fluctuations in currencies other than the
U.S. dollar will greatly benefit trade and industry," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
