<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capital Investment Requests Fall in Israel in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The volume of capital
investment requests dropped by 27 percent in Israel in 1997 to 3.4
billion U.S. dollars from 4.6 billion dollars in 1996, figures
released Wednesday by an investment center showed.
</P>
<P>
Foreign involvement in approved projects also dropped by 42
percent in 1997, according to the center of the Israeli Ministry
of Industry and Trade.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the center approved a total of 444 projects valued
at 2.4 billion dollars in industry, tourism and agriculture
sectors, a drop of 30 percent in number and 3.8 percent in value
respectively compared with that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The center said the decline in investment requests was due in
part to the slowdown in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
In tourism, it said, there was a significant slowdown in
investment, with the number of approvals for new hotels dropping
by 75 percent, and a 23 percent drop in the number of project
implementations compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
The center also attributed the drop to the reduction in
capital investment aid and the high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Many Israeli companies do not have much capital due to the lack
of market conditions for share offerings on the stock exchanges,
the center said, adding that foreigners were investing more in
high-tech companies through share purchases.
</P>
<P>
The center said that in 1998, foreign investment in high-tech
would continue to increase without any connection to the political
situation, since the main export market for these industries is
the United States.
</P>
<P>
But local economists said the stalled Mideast peace process
and the unstable political environment in Israel were the main
reasons for the reduction of investment requests and foreign
capital investment in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
