<HEADLINE> Gansu Becomes Self-sufficient in Farm Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Gansu
Province has become self-sufficient in major agricultural
products, according to the local government.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province harvested 7.66 billion
kilograms of grain in 1997, despite severe natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The grain output reached 8.2 billion kilograms in 1996, setting
the province's grain production record.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than four billion kilograms of grain are in
storage, said Du Ying, director of the provincial grain bureau.
</P>
<P>
Gansu, an undeveloped inland province, has met the cotton
production target three years ahead of time and became
self-sufficient in cotton, with the 1997 output topping 30.25
million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The extension of advanced farming techniques, such as the use of
plastic sheeting, helped the province increase grain production.
</P>
<P>
The province added 27,000 hectares of irrigated farmland and
80,000 hectares of terraced fields in 1997. The advanced
agricultural technique of plastic film has been used on more than
670,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has paid close attention to
supporting such pillar industries as producing raw materials for
beer, medicinal materials, starch and livestock products as well
as production bases for planting lilies, olives, prickly-ash and
alfalfa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the province has determined to construct 40
high-tech agricultural projects, with the purpose of pushing its
agricultural industrialization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
