<HEADLINE> Metallurgical Restructuring Starts with Mergers, Bankruptcies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen Chinese metallurgical
enterprises went bankrupt in 1997, and 38 were involved in mergers.
</P>
<P>
These steps were part of a major restructuring of metallurgical
enterprises, according to officials in the Ministry of
Metallurgical Industry.
</P>
<P>
The 16 bankrupt enterprises had combined assets of 1.746
billion yuan and a total staff of 42,000. The 38 merged
enterprises had total assets of 10.797 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Fifty business firms were involved in the "personnel-reduction-
and-efficiency-enhancement" (FREE) program last year.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 package of merger, bankruptcy and PREE requires the
104 companies to lay off 111,231 workers. Of the total, 66,106
will seek jobs through re-employment centers.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the reform, the Chinese government allowed banks
to write off 2.53 billion yuan, of which 820 million yuan was
listed as bad debts of the 16 bankrupt enterprises, 941 million
yuan for bank interest exemption and 769 million yuan for
settlement allowance.
</P>
<P>
Many large businesses were merged through selling stocks. A
typical example was the merger between the profitable Handan Iron
and Steel Group in north China's Hebei Province and the
debt-ridden Wuyang Iron and Steel Company in central Henan
Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
