<HEADLINE> Chocolate Consumption Low in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The annual output of chocolates
in China has risen from several thousand tons in 1980s to more
than 80,000 tons at present. But per capita consumption of
chocolates by the Chinese people is only one percent of the people
in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
A seminar on the nutritive value of chocolate and its marketing
was held recently. Experts said that the main reason for the low
consumption of chocolates in China is that the overall consumption
level of the Chinese remains low. Another reason was that many
consumers think chocolates may lead to overweight and diseases
such as diabetes.
</P>
<P>
"Their worries are groundless," said some nutriologists,
"Eating an appropriate amount of good-quality chocolate does no
harm to health. Moreover, chocolate can help prevent
cardiovascular diseases and improve body's immunity."
</P>
<P>
However, experts said that the poor quality chocolates produced
by some small enterprises have ruined the reputation of China's
chocolate industry.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar, experts and businessmen appealed that the
standards of chocolate and chocolate products should be perfected
and management over chocolate industry should be improved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
