<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Share Prices End Mixed With Index Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Share prices finished mixed
on the Singapore Market although the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) rose by 14.49 points to close at 1311.4
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that as the Indonesian rupiah fell to an all time
low, investors were spurred to lock in profits.
</P>
<P>
They noted that local and foreign funds continued to nibble
mainly on blue-chip stocks, helping to prop up the STII. In
addition, while property shares rose, bank shares were mostly
lower on renewed fears about their exposures to the Indonesian
economy, which were sparked by the rupiah's fall.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume shrank to 275.42 million units, valued at
462.87 million Singapore dollars (about 262.99 million U.S.
dollars). Declines led advances by 231 to 139, while 239 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded counter as
it registered a turnover of 15.72 million units. It was followed
by the Singapore Technologies Engineering which had 11.83 million
shares traded. MBf Capital was next with 11.35 million shares
traded.
</P>
<P>
Yeo HSS led the gainers of the day as it rose by 62 cents to
finish at 5.6 Singapore dollars. The Singapore Airlines (SIA)
Foreign increased by 60 cents to end at 11.5 Singapore dollars,
while Khong Guan and the Singapore Land were up by 40 cents each
to close at 4.2 and 3.4 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, the Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) was the
biggest loser as it declined by one dollar to end at 16 Singapore
dollars. Creative 50 and the SPH Foreign fell by 70 cents each to
close at 32.8 and 21.9 Singapore dollars respectively. Elec lost
50 cents to finish at 5.5 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
