<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dumped Oil Seen as Hazard in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Millions of liters of
used lubricating oil are dumped down drains or set alight in
South Africa each year, creating an enormous environmental hazard
and causing huge waste in the country, the Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Of the approximately 330 million liters of lubricating oil
purchased in the country each year, less than a fifth is
recovered, the Recovery of Oil Saves the Environment (ROSE)
Foundation, which manages the recovery and recycling of used oil
in South Africa, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from Durban-based FFS Refiners, a leading processor
of waste oil in the country, showed that about 10 percent of used
oil was recovered in 1995, 12 percent in 1996 and an estimated 15
percent last year. This is well below the average rate of 30
percent in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists believe that the improper disposal of used
lubricating oil contributes more to environmental pollution than
all the tanker accidents around the world.
</P>
<P>
A FFS Refiners manager said that the more oil the country
recycles, the more it saves on importing oil. However, only less
than 46,000 tons of used oil was collected in 1996 and the
remainder was poured down the drain or thrown away with the
rubbish, he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the concern of the oil collectors and their call for
more stringent environmental controls, the Water Affairs
Department said that it has not found any major incidence of
deliberate dumping of used lubricants or organic solvents into
water resources.
</P>
<P>
The department said that legislation such as the Water Act and
the Hazardous Substance Act is in place to monitor and control
the dumping of chemical substances, including oil.
</P>
<P>
The dumping of used lubricant oils into domestic drains is
invariably done by do-it-yourself mechanics who do not know the
correct disposal methods, a spokesman of the department said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
