<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Meets With President Of Benin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Qiao Shi, the chairman of the
Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress (NPC), in
a meeting with Benin's President Mathieu Kerekou at Beijing's
Great Hall of the People today, praised the 25 years of effective
cooperation between China and Benin in politics, the economy,
trade, culture, and public health.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said that China appreciates the fact that Benin values
Sino-Beninese relations and that Benin adheres to the one-China
policy and supports China's reunification, and said he is happy
with the good talks on Tuesday between the Chinese and Beninese
presidents.
</P>
<P>
Qiao called President Kerekou an old and popular friend of the
Chinese and said he has supported friendly exchanges between the
NPC Standing Committee and Benin's National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said he believes Sino-Beninese relations, based on the Five
Principles of Peaceful Co-existence, have withstood the test of
the time and can continue to develop.
</P>
<P>
President Kerekou said that he is here to convey to the Chinese
people the good sentiments of the people of Benin, that his visit
has been successful and his talks with President Jiang Zemin good,
and that he believes his visit will advance bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said the NPC is ready to increase exchanges and
cooperation with Benin's National Assembly and to do its part to
increase the good cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Qiao also spoke highly of Benin's achievements under Kerekou's
leadership, and that Benin's government and its people have made
an effort to develop democracy and introduce a legal system and to
govern the country according to law. The government has maintained
political stability and managed to have sustained economic
development and improve people's living standard.
</P>
<P>
Kerekou said that China is a friend of the African people and
has always supported developing countries in safeguarding their
independence and dignity. In the future, he said, developing
countries should continue to help each other, unite, and cooperate
with one another for common development.
</P>
<P>
President Kerekou left here this afternoon for Hainan Province
as part of his China tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
