<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Falls to New Low Against Greenback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah plunged
to a new record low of 12,000 against the U.S. dollar in morning
trading Wednesday from 9,650/9,750 at the close session Tuesday,
but the spot rupiah recovered to close at 11,050/11,400 per
dollar.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time that the rupiah has broken the level of
10,000 per dollar. On January 8, the currency fell to 11,000 per
dollar, compared with 2,400 per dollar in early July last year. On
Tuesday, the spot rupiah opened at 10,100/10,200 against the
dollar and closed at 9,650/9,750.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers contributed the rupiah's weakness to strong
demand for U.S. dollars by local companies to pay maturing
short-term debts and the negative reaction to the criteria set for
Indonesia's vice president candidate by House Speaker Harmoko
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to government estimates, the offshore debt of the
Indonesian private sector was 65 billion dollars as of last
September and most of the loans were short-term debts with a
maturity of between one and two years.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko disclosed Tuesday that President Soeharto was ready to
run for the seventh term.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, the candidate for vice president must have
a vision on science and technology and have deep knowledge of
industry and its usage.
</P>
<P>
The People's Consultative Assembly will convene next March to
elect a president and a vice president and work out state policy
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
As the rupiah fell, stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange
rose 4.01 percent to close at 466.003.  
</P>
</TEXT>
