<HEADLINE> Israeli People Want Peace with Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 21 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli non-governmental
organization is seeking to contact Lebanese civilians in an
attempt to jointly work for an Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon, local newspaper Daily Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview conducted through email with the newspaper,
Shaul Zadka of the "Four Mothers" organization said that there is
nothing to gain from the occupation, which served only to isolate
Israel from its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that if we declare a will to put out, we will
change the average attitude of the Lebanese to Israel. It would
not happen overnight but we have to start building bridges," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The "Four Mothers" was established following the mid-air
Israeli helicopter collision on February 4 last year, in which 65
soldiers and eight airmen were killed.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters were en route to south Lebanon and the crash
was the final straw for four mothers of Israeli soldiers serving
in the occupation zone.
</P>
<P>
"Their children lost a friend in the disaster. They concluded
that it was time to do something about the situation, which has
been dealt with before only by the military and political
establishments," Zadka said.
</P>
<P>
"Thousands of people signed our petitions and hundreds are
registered as members, many of them activists," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We are organizing various activities which include
demonstrations, picket lines every Friday on the main road
junctions in the country, participating in panels, as well as
lobbying politicians and ex-officers and maintaining constant
contact with the press in Israel and abroad," he added.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, the organization announced it would seek to
contact Lebanese civilians to lobby for an Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"We want them (the Lebanese) to believe us, if not the
(Lebanese) government, and understand our leaving their country
is not only for the sake of our soldiers but for the future
relations between the two countries," Zadka said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985 when Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer
security zone in south Lebanon, clashes between Lebanese
resistance groups fighting for the ouster of the Israelis, and
Israeli troops have never stopped.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, 192 people were killed and more than 300 wounded
in the clashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
