<HEADLINE> Shanghai Strengthens Protection of Copyright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial center, has spared no effort to strengthen its
protection of copyright in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The city opened its first copyright office some 10 years ago,
and has since established several special organizations and
societies to effectively protect the copyrights of local authors.
</P>
<P>
An official with the municipal copyright protection department
said that the vast majority of the city's publishers, printers and
editors have attended on-the-job training classes covering the
protection of copyright.
</P>
<P>
The city has also hosted several symposiums on copyright
protection and regularly publicizes the copyright information
on television and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has successfully handled over 20 major copyright
cases, including a case involving the work entitled New Concept
English, a popular book for Chinese citizens learning English.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the city's legal environment has
resulted in a booming copyright industry, with the number of
copyright contracts signed annually rising from less than a dozen
in previous years to over 120 at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
