<HEADLINE> Parliamentary Investigation Urged Against Former </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish deputy has started
collecting petitions among the lawmakers in a bid to launch a
parliamentary probe into former prime minister Tansu Ciller over
the slush fund scandal.
</P>
<P>
Fikri Saglar, deputy of the Republican People' Party, said
that so long as one tenth of the parliamentarians sign the
petition, the Parliament has to open an investigation against
Ciller, Turkish Daily News said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the parliament rules, the job of collecting petitions
must be completed within ten days.
</P>
<P>
Saglar said that the ruling of a lower Turkish court had
proven that Ciller, chairwoman of the opposition True Path Party
(DYP) misused the slush fund while she was prime minister.
</P>
<P>
If more than half of the deputies vote for the probe,
Ciller will have to stand trial in the Constitutional Court on
charges of malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
The lower court ruling said that Ciller was swindled out
of thousands of U.S. dollars by a man who purported to be
a close friend of her. The sum of money was part of the
slush fund.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's High Appeals Court upheld the ruling later,
increasing the possibility of a judicial probe into the Ciller
case.
</P>
<P>
"The High Appeals Court decision has proved that the slush
funds were allocated outside their purposes," Saglar said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Ciller had said that she was not afraid of
any kind of investigations, adding such allegation would only
make the DYP stronger.
</P>
<P>
Last year, some parties in the parliament tried to launch
a corruption investigation against Ciller, but the attempt was
smashed by then coalition government formed by DYP and the
pro-Islamic Welfare Party led by Necmettin Erbakan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
