<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares were
Wednesday weakened by fears of further financial instability in
Asia, particularly Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 16.6 points lower at 2622.8,
having relinquished an earlier high of 2,622.8.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah hit a record low Wednesday, dipping in
early trade to 11,500 to 11,800 to the US dollar, on political and
economic concerns and strong demand for the US currency.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 28.1 points to 4523.8.
</P>
<P>
Swimming against the broader market, News Corp soared on a buy
recommendation put forward by leading US broking house Morgan
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
News Corp ordinary shares jumped 51 cents to 9.41 Australian
dollars on turnover of 7.8 million shares while the preferred
shares vaulted 34 cents to 8.03 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were generally weak, with the banking index
falling 70.4 points to 5577.9.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank lead the way down with a fall of 50.8
cents to 21.13 Australian dollars, while Westpac bank dropped 14.8
cents to 10.292 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank fell 15 cents to 9.97 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank shares rose against the trend, adding two
cents to 18.50 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 7.3 points to 1102.4 with mixed
fortunes among the major stocks.
</P>
<P>
BHP fell 28 cents to 13.72 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Rio Tinto rose 39.8 cents to 18.598
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index improved 11.2 points to 1029.5 as bullion
increased 1.75 US dollars per ounce to 290.05 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover Wednesday was 307.85 million shares worth
656.69 million US dollars with falls outnumbering rises 597 to
492.  
</P>
