<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, January 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton started the second
round of talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over
his fresh ideas aimed at pulling the derailed Middle East peace
process back on track.
</P>
<P>
During the first round of the 90-minute talks between the U.S.
and Israeli leaders Tuesday morning, Clinton said the United
States believed the important thing "would be a credible
withdrawal plan" for a pullback of the Israeli troops from its
occupied West Bank, a senior administration official
said. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told reporters
after her separate meeting with the Israeli prime minister that
the talks were "very useful" but gaps remains on various issues.
(US-Israel-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Two commandos were injured on Tuesday during a police
rebellion in Shkodra, a large town in northern Albania.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said that about ten rebel policemen
carrying machine guns rushed into the streets at 11:30 a.m. (local
time) and fired shot in the air. Later, the rebels opened fire on
the Shkodra police station and exchanged fire with the police in
the station. Two commandos were wounded and two rebels were
arrested during the clash. However, a report from the Interior
Ministry said in the evening that the situation in Shkodra had
returned to normal and all the key organs of the town were under
control of the local police and the commandos coming from
Tirana. (Albania-Police Riot)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- The market monitoring committee of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) will convene a meeting in
Vienna to discuss measures to prevent the drop in oil prices,
Farouk Muhammed, the spokesman for OPEC confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The committee, composed of oil ministers from Nigeria, Kuwait
and Iran, is responsible for insuring that OPEC members comply
with quotas. According to Muhammed, the market monitoring
committee meeting scheduled for January 26 could become a special
ministerial meeting if OPEC ministers from countries other than
the three mentioned attend the meeting. (OPEC-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia, in trying to resolve the Middle East crisis,
welcome any efforts to revive the peace process there, Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Gennady Tarasov said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Tarasov said Russia was keeping
close contact with the United States and other Middle East
nations. On the Russian part, Tarasov said, a Russian-Palestine
joint commission will meet early February, and Moscow will take
further steps to prompt all parties to revive the deadlocked peace
process. (Russia-Mideast)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- If the Baltic countries' bid to join NATO becomes a
reality, this would definitely lead to a review of Russia's
relations with NATO, Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady
Tarasov said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Russia's stance toward the charter, Tarasov stressed at his
Tuesday news briefing, would depend on how its implementation
affected security and stability in the Baltic region and
Europe. Four days ago the three Baltic states, Estonia, Latvia and
Lithuania, signed a partnership charter with the United States in
Washington. Though no timetable has been set, the U.S. voiced in
the charter its support for the Baltic countries' admission into
NATO. (Russia-Baltic-NATO) 
</P>
</TEXT>
