<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Price Fall May Delay UAE Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The slide in world oil
prices might delay the announcement of the UAE federal budget, a
local newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Financial sources said that the downturn in oil prices ...
might delay the issue of the federal budget because officials have
to review initial estimates concerning revenues for this budget,"
the Arabic-language Asharq Al-Awsat reported.
</P>
<P>
Oil earnings account for nearly two thirds of the UAE's total
revenues each year. Estimates on oil prices are decisive for the
Gulf country to formulate its budget.
</P>
<P>
World crude prices have fallen dramatically in the past weeks
to around 15 dollars a barrel, the lowest level since mid-1994.
Such a level is much lower than the widely projected 16 dollars a
barrel by the Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
The price collapse has forced Iran, another Gulf state to
reconsider its initially-made budget. Informed sources here said
most of the other oil-reliant Gulf countries have also begun to
review their budgets.
</P>
<P>
Officials and experts attributed the collapse to some bearish
factors including declined Asian demand cause by a currency
crisis, an unusually warm winter in the northern hemisphere and
the return of sanctions-hit Iraq to oil markets.
</P>
<P>
Another key factor is the agreement signed by the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries in November last year to increase
the group's official output ceiling by 10 percent to 27.5 million
barrels a day. The deal has given buyers confidence to bet on
ample supply and low prices in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
