<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Uses More Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, an
economic power house of China, is expected to set a new record in
the use of overseas funds in the past year, provincial foreign
trade officials predicted.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that in the first 11 months of last year, the
southern China province utilized 12.94 billion US dollars in
overseas funds, a year-on-year rise of 10.26 percent.
</P>
<P>
Officials estimated the figure for the whole year at over 13.9
billion US dollars for 1996. It will be the fourth consecutive
year that the province's use of foreign capital surpasses 10
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Guangdong had utilized a total of 81
billion US dollars in foreign funds, with an average annual growth
of over 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign funds have not only supplied over one quarter of the
money needed for its construction, but also provided jobs for
about 10 million people, generated over 40 billion yuan (4.82
billion US dollars) in tax revenues for the central and local
governments, and helped the province to contribute about 40
percent of the country's exports, up from about 10 percent
previously.
</P>
<P>
The province has attracted investors from over 70 countries and
region to pump funds into its agriculture, industry, and service
sector in the forms of direct investment, and processing and
assembling with supplied materials, samples or parts, and the
compensation trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to Surmount Financial Crisis: Philippine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said on Wednesday that he was firmly convinced that Asia would
soon surmount the financial crisis and resume its dynamic economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a yearly foreign correspondent conference in
Manila, Ramos said the financial storm, which started from
Thailand in June last year, has brought difficulties to economies
of Southeast Asian nations, South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he believed that Asian nations would soon
enough surmount the crisis, adding "it was just a matter of when".
</P>
<P>
For the part of the Philippines, Ramos said the country was
"less stricken" than its neighbors in the current financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It should be said that we have not suffered here the collapse
of financial institutions and customer panic that has happened in
other Asian countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
But given the uncertainties facing the country and the region,
he said, the Philippines must take measures to ensure that this
crisis would not paralyze the economy and inflict more harm upon
the people.
</P>
<P>
Although foreign borrowing by the private sector and rapid
credit expansion was relatively short in the country, and limits
were set on real estate loans, the country must work to strengthen
its capital markets and financial institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Second, we must continue with our tight monetary policy that
has helped sustain a low inflation environment, maintained price
stability and kept money supply within targets," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos added that the government would also cut its spending by
implementing fiscal austerity measures, promote export growth as
the key to recovery and continue with its various structural
reforms.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, Ramos also said that the country would
have honest, peaceful and orderly elections in May this year and
that he would step down as his term expires in June this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
