<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big U.S. Banks, Securities Firms Report Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Most big banks and
securities firms of the United States Tuesday reported higher
earnings for the fourth quarter of 1997, despite "difficult market
conditions in Asia," said news reports here.
</P>
<P>
Chase Manhattan Corp., the nation's largest bank, said earnings
rose to 874 million U.S. dollars, or up by 4.5 percent, in the
fourth quarter, from 836 million dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Citicorp, the second largest bank, said net earnings rose to
1.06 billion dollars, or increased by seven percent, from 987
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bank of New York had biggest percentage of profit increase
among the banks. It said net earnings rose to 298 million dollars,
or up by 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
Similar results were also reported by large U.S. securities
firms.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the second-largest securities firm, said
that its profit was up by five percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that strong markets in the United States and
Europe helped offset difficult conditions in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Although Asia dampened profits at many Wall Street firms in the
fourth quarter, it did not stop them from posting exceptional
results for the year as investors and companies were captivated by
the raging bull market, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
