<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Sector in Northeast China Recovering From Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- State-owned enterprises in
Liaoning Province, a leading industrial area in northeast China,
ended an eight-year period of economic losses in 1997, a
provincial official reports.
</P>
<P>
State-owned firms produced 66 million yuan in profits last year
and a combined output value of 152.3 billion yuan, a 10-percent
rise over the previous year's figure. The number of money-losing
firms dropped by 63 and their losses fell by 350 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The official attributes the changes to adjustments in the
industrial structure over the past two years, when 139 small firms
were merged with others, 162 poorly-managed enterprises declared
bankruptcy, and 60 large enterprise groups were built. Over 80
percent of small and medium-sized state-owned enterprises have
changed their property rights and management systems.
</P>
<P>
As a result, state assets worth 17 billion yuan were put to use
again and liabilities were down an average of 4.3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
The province spent 24 billion yuan on technology changes last
year.
</P>
<P>
To address the problem of workers laid off by state-owned
enterprises, 155 re-employment centers have been set up, providing
new jobs for a million people, or half the unemployed workers in
Liaoning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 07:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Build Five New Cities by 2015: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait will build five new
cities to tackle housing and service problems under a proposed
plan for a growing population within 17 years, a senior official
said.
</P>
<P>
According to local Arab Times Wednesday, Director of the Third
Kuwait Master Plan Waleed Al-Jassim said Kuwait is swiftly heading
for an enormous shortage of housing and services unless the
government endorses and executes the plan.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures projected a population increase of 1.6
million, or 70 percent, from the current 2.2 million to 3.8
million by the year of 2015.
</P>
<P>
Al-Jassim said "our projections show that Kuwait requires
357,970 new houses and apartments by the year 2015," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait's metropolitan area has nearly reached the
maximum tolerable density, indicating that new cities are needed
to build houses for the people.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the only way for the government to solve the
growing housing shortage is to transfer initiative for
construction to the private sector and prospective house owners.
</P>
<P>
The Third Kuwait Master Plan lays down the country's planning
strategy for the period between 1995 to 2015, but it has yet to be
endorsed by the government.
</P>
<P>
He said he expected the plan to clear all remaining
administrative and technical hurdles by the beginning of next
year.
</P>
<P>
However, he also regretted that "too many committees and
bodies are involved in the decision making process, while too
many people are waiting for housing" in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
