<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists: Latin America, Market for U.S. West Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Latin America could be an
alternative for California in the United States West Coast as
eastern Asian market is sagging, some economists said.
</P>
<P>
In a report released last week, a team of economists from Bank
of America, California's largest and third-largest in the United
States, said that Latin America could make up the expected decline
in California's exports to Asia.
</P>
<P>
California's exports to all markets are forecast to reach 113.5
billion U.S. dollars this year, up three billion dollars from that
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
As exports to the Asian countries account for slightly more
than half of its total, the state will be more affected by the
Asian economic slowdown than the rest of the United States, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the economists said, higher interest rates in
Asian countries will affect the region's ability to import capital
goods, which make up a high percentage of California's exports. If
economic conditions in the Asian countries worsen, California's
export growth will be reduced from the current estimates.
</P>
<P>
Set against this backdrop, Latin America becomes more
attractive a destination for California exports in 1998, the
economists said.
</P>
<P>
The report expects California's exports to the region to grow
by 17 percent to 16.7 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Noting the region's increasing demand for electronic products,
computers, telecommunication networks and related equipment as
well as automotive and infrastructure equipment, the report said
that the massive privatization of key state-owned industries in
Brazil, Mexico and Argentina will sustain the high demand for
California's capital export products.
</P>
<P>
"The current economic environment provides an ideal time for
exporters to explore means of tapping the growing potential of the
Lation America market," the report said.
</P>
<P>
California used to have little interest in opening trade with
the region. Outside Mexico, which is California's third-largest
trading partner, Latin America right now accounts for less than
one percent of the state's total exports.
</P>
<P>
But things have been changing as seen in the first half of last
year, when California's exports to Brazil, Argentina and Chile
jumped by nine percent over the previous year, and exports to
Colombia, Venezuela, Peru and Ecuador increased by 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
While with an eye on Latin America's growth of capital,
stability of markets and increasing size of the middle class,
business executives here minded each other with the pitfalls in
doing business in the region.
</P>
<P>
They also mentioned poor infrastructure, currency crisis
particularly in Brazil and drop in oil price, which will hurt many
Latin American countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
