<HEADLINE> Philippoussis Crashes Out, Fromberg Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Mark Philippoussis crashed to
a humiliating defeat while fellow Australian Richard Fromberg
pulled out a career-best performance at the Australian Open today.
</P>
<P>
In a match he should have and could have won, Philippoussis was
out-served, out-run and generally outplayed by a
moderately-performed Moroccan with a greater will to win.
</P>
<P>
Hicham Arazi, a 24-year-old from Casablanca, beat Philippoussis
1-6, 6-2, 4-6, 6-1, 9-7 in a second round match that left the
Australian short on explanations.
</P>
<P>
For Fromberg, the second round brought a victory he said was
one of the most important of his career and his best in a grand
slam.
</P>
<P>
He beat last year's runner-up and seventh seed Carlos Moya of
Spain 4-6, 6-4, 7-6, 6-4, ending a year of frustration and
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
As a result he came into today's match ranked 56th against
Moya's ninth.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Venus Williams defeated her younger sister Serena
Williams 7-6, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
The pair, braided, black and blessed with talent, slugged it
out on center court before a crowd which was not sure who to
cheer.
</P>
<P>
In the opening set they traded service breaks but Venus, 17,
quickly took control as 16-year-old Serena succumbed to a knee
injury, a legacy from last week's Aadidas International in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The two are intent on wasting little time marching to the top
of the world rankings in women's tennis and this match is sure to
be the first of many between them.
</P>
<P>
"What you saw today was something for the future to watch,"
Serena said later.
</P>
<P>
While the attention was on the extrovert duo, fellow American
Lindsay Davenport was involved in a titanic fight on an outside
court with Slovakian Karina Habsudova.
</P>
<P>
The No.2 seed eventually clawed her way through to the third
round, beating Habsudova 2-6, 6-0, 9-7.
</P>
<P>
Australia's day was completed by the defeat of Australian Scott
Draper who went down 7-6, 6-3, 6-3 to sixth seed Petr Korda of the
Czech Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
