<HEADLINE> ADB Assures Philippines of More Financial Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Manila-based Asian
Development Bank (ADB) assured Wednesday the Philippine government
of its full support to help the country weather its current
currency problems similarly plaguing other Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
In a working breakfast meeting with President Fidel Ramos, ADB
president Mitsuo Sato said the ADB is also preparing in 1998 more
assistance to the country in the event that the government may
require additional bank resources.
</P>
<P>
Sato reaffirmed ADB's commitment to the country to make
available the bank's financial and technical resources to assist
the government in overcoming the present difficulties and reaching
the social and economic goals and objectives set out in
Philippines 2000.
</P>
<P>
He added that the ADB has granted from 1992 to 1997 a total of
long term loans of two billion U.S. dollars to the Philippines, in
addition to some 38 million in grant assistance.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, he said, the ADB has lined up 500 million U.S. dollars
in total assistance to the country for various environment,
agriculture, education projects.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has indicated that at present there would seem
to be no immediate requirement for the provision of large-scale
balance of payments support by the ADB in the current currency
crisis.
</P>
<P>
ADB vice president Peter Sullivan said the ADB believes that
the Philippine government has managed the currency crisis
effectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
