<HEADLINE> NZ Accommodation Industry Hit by Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wellington, January 21 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's accommodation
industry has been hit by the shockwaves from the Asian financial
crisis and the domestic economic slowdown, shows figures released
by Statistics NZ Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the office indicates that occupancy rates
in all types of accommodation, except caravan parks and
campgrounds, fell by more than five percentage points late last
year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics NZ said that overall, the national occupancy rate
fell to 52.5 percent in November last year from 57.8 percent one
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Total guest nights -- the number of stays in hotels, motels,
bed-and-breakfasts, and hostels dropped nationally by about
100,000 nights to 1.79 million.
</P>
<P>
But it was "hosted" accommodation such as homestays and
bed-and-breakfasts, took the heaviest blow in last November,
falling from 35.2 percent to 28.5 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
