<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Netanyahu Start Second Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton started the second round of talks with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over his fresh ideas aimed at
pulling the derailed Middle East peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
During the first round of the 90-minute talks between the U.S.
and Israeli leaders Tuesday morning, Clinton said the United
States believed the important thing "would be a credible
withdrawal plan" for a pullback of the Israeli troops from its
occupied West Bank, a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told reporters after
her separate meeting with the Israeli prime minister that the
talks were "very useful" but gaps remains on various issues.
</P>
<P>
"There are gaps. We are trying to narrow those gaps,"
Albright said. "I think we're doing well, given the fact that
we're working on very, very difficult issues."
</P>
<P>
"What we are talking about are the appropriate elements for a
further redeployment -- that is timing, the quality, quantity
and, of course, security aspects involved in that," she said.
</P>
<P>
Before the second round of the talks, Netanyahu told Fox News
Channel that he had discussed with Clinton and Albright an
agreement to cede certain territory to the Palestinians under the
condition that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat keeps his promises
to crack down Muslim extremists.
</P>
<P>
It is "a deal... in which as the Palestinians comply with their
promises, Israel withdraws from territory that is not vital to its
defenses," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Netanyahu had brought with him a modest offer to
Clinton on Israel's pullback from the West Bank, which was
occupied by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
"We're prepared to conduct a further redeployment to advance
the peace process, provided we don't touch on Israel's basic
security requirements," he said during the interview with Fox.
</P>
<P>
He also ruled out any possibility to meet with Arafat on
Thursday when the Palestinian leader came to Washington for
talks with Clinton on the same subject. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
