<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Officials Asked to Declare Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government has
asked all government officials to submit immediately their annual
return of assets in a bid to ensure accountability and
transparency in the conduct of civil servants, the local press
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Establishment recently issued a circular asking
government officials at all levels to submit their annual return
of assets and declare their properties in accordance with the
Government Servant (Conduct) Rules 1979.
</P>
<P>
Officials working with ministries, departments and directorates
shall submit their papers to the Discipline and Inquiry Cell under
the Ministry of Establishment headed by Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina, the circular was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Newly recruited government officials have been asked to make a
declaration, at the time of entering the public service, of all
movable and immovable properties held by themselves or by members
of their families, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Section 13 of the rules stipulates that "Every government
servant shall make a declaration to the government ... of all
immovable and movable properties belonging to or held by him or
her or a member of his or her family" when entering government
service and "submit to the government ... an annual return of
assets ... showing any increase of property afterwards."
</P>
<P>
In most cases, however, the rules have not been adhered to by
government officials, the circular said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
