<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Riot in Northern Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Two commandos were injured on
Tuesday during a police rebellion in Shkodra, a large town in
northern Albania.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said that about ten rebel policemen
carrying machine guns rushed into the streets at 11:30 a.m. (local
time) and fired shot in the air.
</P>
<P>
Later, the rebels opened fire on the Shkodra police station and
exchanged fire with the police in the station. Two commandos were
wounded and two rebels were arrested during the clash.
</P>
<P>
One report said that several armed rebels entered the Shkodra
government building, holding some officials hostage and ordering
the local police chief and his commandos to leave Shkodra.
</P>
<P>
However, a report from the Interior Ministry said in the
evening that the situation in Shkodra had returned to normal
and all the key organs of the town were under control of the local
police and the commandos coming from Tirana.
</P>
<P>
The riot was crushed, said the ministry, adding that all the
rebels had been suspects of some smuggling and robbery cases.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Shkodra, a strong base of the current largest
opposition party, the Democratic Party, remained strained in
recent days when the Interior Ministry dismissed and replaced the
town's police chief and dispatched a group of commandos.
</P>
<P>
The riot broke out when the new police chief started an
investigation into a number of smuggling and robbery cases in
which some local policemen were involved.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, the Democratic Party accused the current
government of making vindictive attacks on the opposition and
called for the withdrawal of the new police chief and his
commandos to avoid more clashes.
</P>
<P>
However, the ruling Socialist Party charged the local leader of
the Democratic Party for instigating the riot and asked law
enforcement agencies to check into all anti-government activities.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party also called on the people in Shkodra to
draw a clear line of demarcation between themselves and the
criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
