<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC to Issue Hong Kong Dollar Medium-Term Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) announced Tuesday the issue of 300 million bond
notes denominated in Hong Kong dollar on January 16.
</P>
<P>
The issue, equivalent to some 38.76 million U.S. dollars, is
under the Global Medium-Term Note program of the IFC, a member of
the World Bank Group headquartered in this U.S. capital.
</P>
<P>
With an issue price of 99.80 percent, the two-year notes carry
a quarterly coupon of 11.50 percent per annum. And their proceeds
are to be swapped into U.S. dollar floating rate funds.
</P>
<P>
The sole lead manager is the Societe Generale Asia Limited.
</P>
<P>
The planned transaction, said an IFC news release, will bring
the IFC's market borrowing to about 1,986 million U.S. dollars for
the fiscal year 1998, which started on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is the largest multilateral source of financing for
private sector projects in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
