<HEADLINE> Kohl, of Germany, in Rome for Italy's Euro Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl held informal talks
Tuesday on the future of Europe and the monetary union.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, here on a five-hour visit, said the planned single
European currency, to be named euro, "will arrive and will
continue on it track and no one will stop it."
</P>
<P>
"The construction of the European home will continue to move
forward," the German chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
After the adoption of the new currency on January 1, 1999,
"even those who are against it today will claim that they had
always been in favor of the single currency," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Kohl was facing heavy pressure to support
Italy's aspiration of joining the first wave of European Union
countries switching over to the single currency system.
</P>
<P>
Apparently referring to speculations that Germany opposed Italy
in the euro, Kohl said "there is too much comment on something
which has not taken place, and this seems absurd to me."
</P>
<P>
On his part, Prodi said Italy and Germany share a "common
objective of building Europe" and both want Europe to be
economically strong and politically united.
</P>
<P>
A united Europe must be governed by strict criteria and this
was "not only in Germany's interest, but also at this historic
moment, in Italy's," Prodi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
