<HEADLINE> Dhaka Takes Measures to Improve Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
allocated 118.6 million taka (2.62 million U.S. dollars) to
implement six projects to save the country from environment
degradation, local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed recently by Forest and Environment Minister
Syeda Sajeda Chowdhury in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The projects included development of regional laboratories and
infrastructures, formulation of a national environmental program,
the phase-out of ozone depleting substances and the building of a
national integrated information system on environment in
Bangladesh, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The government had also carried out plans to improve the
environment of the country's capital, Dhaka, including programs to
control the pollution from industrial units and vehicles, she
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government had spent 406.1 million taka
(9 million dollars) during the period between January 1996 and
June 1997 to implement an afforestation program to maintain
ecological balance in the country.  
</P>
