<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Make Further Talks with Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said on Tuesday that President Bill Clinton would have a
further discussion with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
over some U.S. fresh ideas for salvaging the moribund Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The president has presented some ideas. We have been
elaborating on them for the prime minister," Albright told
reporters after a separate, two-hour meeting with the Israeli
leader.
</P>
<P>
She said the two leaders would meet for a second time later on
Tuesday to discuss all these fresh ideas. U.S. and Israeli
officials said the second session will take place at about 9:45
EST (0245 GMT on Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
Albright said the talks between Clinton and Netanyahu was "very
useful" but she admitted there were gaps remaining on various
issues.
</P>
<P>
And White House spokesman Mike McCurry also said a lot of hard
work remained to be addressed after the first 90-minute session
this morning between Clinton and Netanyahu. "We didn't anticipate
the heavens to open today," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States believes the further withdrawal of the
Israeli troops from the West Band is one of the important things
for the Middle East peace process to be pulled back on track.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton offered his view, during his talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the White House on
Tuesday, that the United States believed the important thing
"would be a credible withdrawal plan" for redeploying Israeli
troops from the occupied West Bank, a senior U.S. official said
after U.S. and Israeli leaders meeting.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin also said Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright reiterated the U.S. view that "in order
for us to put all the pieces of the Middle East peace process back
together, one of the important pieces is the further redeployment."
</P>
<P>
He said the United States had hoped that Israel could offer a
sizable and credible pullback of the West Bank, that was helpful
in pushing peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
"With respect to further redeployment, we do believe that it
needs to take place in a way that it is credible, that the size
needs to be significant," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said after his talks with Clinton that there was no
breakthrough for any redeployment of the Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
"We are now looking for a joint formula to advance the peace
process ... No agreement has yet been formulated," he told Israel
television in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Rubin did not disclose what size of pullback the United States
believe was needed for pulling together the pieces of peace
process. But according some reports, the United States proposed a
12 percent of the West Bank to be handed over to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu was said to have brought a modest offer of 9
percent of the Israeli-occupied West Bank to the Palestinians,
which certainly falls short of U.S. expectation and even far away
from the demand of the Palestinian leader Yasir Arafat, who said
Israel should yield 80 or 90 percent of the territory and half of
jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Before his talks with Netanyahu, Clinton indicated he was not
planning to pressure the Israeli leader on the issue of
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
"I think what we ought to talk about is what both sides can do
now," he said at a photo session with Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also confirmed that neither the U.S. president nor
his aides had tried to apply under pressure on him to make
concessions.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth time that Clinton met with Netanyahu.
Clinton, claiming to be the sponsor of the Middle East peace
process, has not been very happy with Netanyahu constantly turning
a deaf ear to U.S. repeated warning over Israel's moves that were
in contradiction with Oslo agreements.
</P>
<P>
With regard to israel's unilateral action of establishing
Jewish settlements in the West Bank, Rubin said the U.S. view was
that this kind of unilateral action could only "make it difficult
to create an environment for the negotiations and make it harder
to create success in those negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians has
almost been collapsed because of Israel's decision to build Jewish
housing units in Arab East Jerusalem and refusal to withdraw from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
After failures of U.S. mediations by its envoy Dennis Ross and
Albright, Clinton has to come out to deal directly with Netanyahu
and Arafat, whom Clinton will meet on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
