<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tightens Security Before Independence Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Checks on all vehicles coming
from the east to the west and south has been doubled as Sri Lankan
police are on high alert two weeks before the golden jubilee
celebrations of the country's independence on February 4.
</P>
<P>
Police said Wednesday that they are sparing no effort to ensure
there will be no sabotage or violence during the celebrations. The
main function will be held in the ancient capital city of Kandy to
mark the 50th Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
They said rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
might seek every chance to stage attacks. Police are paying
particular attention to all kinds of vehicles running from the
north and east to Colombo and Kandy.
</P>
<P>
All trucks moving from Batticaloa, Eastern Province, to Colombo
have to park for 24 hours at a military check point near
Batticaloa for inspection.
</P>
<P>
Goods on the trucks will be unloaded and a thorough search will
be conducted to make sure they carry no bombs.
</P>
<P>
During the whole of last week there had been no major incident
by the LTTE against the security forces in Batticaloa district.
Police said they need to maintain an even higher alert as they
feel this could be the "calm before the storm."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
