<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Series to Stage History of Dunhuang Grottoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A 12-part TV documentary,
featuring the famous Dunhuang Grottoes in northwest China, will
begin shooting next month.
</P>
<P>
Audiences are expected to have a glance at the brilliance of
the Dunhuang arts through the TV series in May, 2000, when China
will mark the 100th anniversary of the discovery of this
combination of natural and man-made wonder, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
Sandwiched between snow-capped peaks and sand of the Gobi
Desert in northwest China, the 1,600-year-old Dunhuang possesses
the largest and most extraordinary art gallery in the world. Some
500 caves have been found completely covered in 45,000 square
meters of frescoes.
</P>
<P>
More than three-fourths of Dunhuang's 40,000-plus cultural
relics are now scattered outside China.
</P>
<P>
The TV documentary will shed light on the historic cultural
exchanges among the world's family of human beings, exemplified by
the magnanimity and openness of the flourishing Han (206 BC-220
AD) and Tang (618-907) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
It will also explore cultural exchanges between the west and
the east, trace Buddhism's movement from the east to the west, and
view the relationship among nationalities in northwest China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
