<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Warns Against Baltic Entry Into NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 20 (Xinhua) -- If the Baltic countries' bid to
join NATO becomes a reality, this would definitely lead to a
review of Russia's relations with NATO, Russian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Gennady Tarasov said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Four days ago the three Baltic states, Estonia, Latvia and
Lithuania, signed a partnership charter with the United States in
Washington. Though no timetable has been set, the U.S. voiced in
the charter its support for the Baltic countries' admission into
NATO.
</P>
<P>
Russia's stance toward the charter, Tarasov stressed at his
Tuesday news briefing, would depend on how its implementation
affected security and stability in the Baltic region and Europe.
</P>
<P>
He said the document does not refer to Russia's offer to reduce
its number of troops, or its proposal for strengthening security
and stability in the Baltic region.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin last October revealed Russia's
security plans for the Baltic, but the plans fell on deaf
ears. Tarasov said Russia wished that concrete Baltic security
measures would be based on Moscow's proposals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
