<HEADLINE> Russia Welcomes Efforts to Revive Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia in trying to resolve the
Middle East crisis welcome any efforts to revive the peace process
there, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Gennady Tarasov said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Tarasov said Russia was keeping
close contact with the United States and other Middle East nations.
</P>
<P>
Following the Tuesday talks with Netanyahu in Washington,
Clinton was scheduled to meet Palestinian President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
On the Russian part, Tarasov said, a Russian-Palestine joint
commission will meet early February, and Moscow will take further
steps to prompt all parties to revive the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, resolving the Middle East issue calls for
joint efforts by Russia, the United States and other countries.
</P>
<P>
About the latest standoff between United Nations arms
inspectors and Iraqi authorities, he said Russia had submitted a
list of 60 Russian experts available to work on inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
Russia is ready to provide an aircraft to the U.N. commission
in charge of dismantling Iraq's nuclear, chemical and biological
weapons facilities for flying monitoring missions over Iraq, the
spokesman said. 
</P>
