<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Asks for Further Gulf War Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government recently
asked the United Nation Compensation Commission (UNCC) for another
95 million US dollars in compensation for damage during the Gulf
War, according to the Thai Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The request follows the earlier approval by the Geneva-based
UNCC of more than 24 million US dollars in compensation for 6,298
Thai people who had to return to Thailand from Iraq and Kuwait
during the Gulf War, Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Thinnakorn
Kannasutra was quoted Wednesday by the local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new request concerns damage to 173 Thai agencies, most of
which were private companies, he added. The Department of
Employment, which asked for more than 6 million US dollars, is the
sole government agency involved.
</P>
<P>
"Consideration for the new request may take more time because
the commission has to investigate a lot of evidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Labor and Social Welfare Ministry submitted the earlier
request for 24 million US dollars in 1992 through the Thai
Permanent Mission in Geneva.  
</P>
</TEXT>
