<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Farm Ministers to Discuss Banana Regime, Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
agriculture ministers met Tuesday on new proposals for a banana
regime and continuing ban on the imports of hormone-treated beef.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting here was the first of the kind since
Britain took over the rotating EU presidency in January.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Farm Minister Jack Cunningham said the banana regime
was particularly important to Britain. "Reaching agreement on this
dossier will be a high priority for my presidency," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new banana proposals involve scrapping the current import
license system, which has been under attach for allegedly favoring
fruit from former British and French colonies.
</P>
<P>
It has also been proposed that the EU grants aid to African,
Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) growers to help them maintain a
competitive edge against larger Latin American producers.
</P>
<P>
The World Trade Organization (WTO), which ruled that the old
banana regime broke free trading regulations, has given the EU
until January 1999 to modify its policy.
</P>
<P>
However, EU sources said no decisions were likely to be made
during the single-day discussions by EU agriculture ministers.
</P>
<P>
The top agriculture officials are expected to focus on the
proposed easing of the ban on British beef exports, which has been
imposed because of the so-called "mad cow disease."
</P>
<P>
They also planned to discuss recent outbreaks of swine fever in
Germany and Spain. The Belgian government said Monday it was
closing its door to pigs from Germany due to such an outbreak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
