<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Demand for Dollars Sends Indonesian Rupiah Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The high demand for U.S.
dollars from local companies dragged the Indonesian rupiah
(national currency) down further Tuesday to a new low of 10,500
against the greenback in morning trade, dealers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the rupiah break the level of 10,000
per dollar. On January 8, the rupiah fell to 11,000 per dollar,
bringing the loss of the rupiah to 300 percent of its value
against the U.S. dollar since July last year.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah managed to recover in the afternoon on news that the
German government would help Indonesia settle offshore loans in
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The spot rupiah recovered to close at 9,650/9,975 in Jakarta
against an opening of 10,100/10,200.
</P>
<P>
Horst Kohler, a special envoy of Germany's Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, said here Tuesday he would propose to Kohl to ask German
banks to con-tribute constructively to a solution to the foreign
debt problem of the Indonesian private sector.
</P>
<P>
Kohler, who is leading a special German delegation here to
assess Indonesia's economic situation, said finding a rapid
solution to Indonesia's private offshore debt was of crucial
importance in dealing with the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to a government estimate, the offshore debt of the
Indonesian private sector was 65 billion U.S. dollars as of
September last year. Most of the loans were short-term debts with
a maturity of between one and two years.
</P>
<P>
As the rupiah fell, stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange
rose 2.05 percent, supported by a late rally on banking stocks on
expectations of more bank mergers and buoyant trading in blue-ship
stocks, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The composite index surged 9.01 points to 448.91 Tuesday from
439.01 the previous day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
