<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barents Council Calls for Close Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Barents Euro-Arctic
Council Tuesday called on member states to improve cooperation in
the northernmost part of Europe.
</P>
<P>
In its 5th ministerial meeting in Lulea, Sweden, the council
reviewed political, economic, environmental and social changes in
the Nordic area since the council was formed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The council also called for further cooperation among member
countries in the fields of trade, energy, health, tourism,
transport, culture, protecting indigenous people and nuclear
safety.
</P>
<P>
A press communique, released after the meeting, said the
increased cooperation within the area constitutes an integral part
of the effort to create a stable, secure and prosperous Europe.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission backs cooperation in the Barents region
as a means to promote peace, prosperity, stability and security,
as well as to strengthen links between the EU and its neighbors,
said the communique.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, more than 300 million ECU has been made available
to the region.
</P>
<P>
Six foreign ministers of member states and an EU commissioner
for external relations attended the meeting. Other participants
were senior representatives from observer nations, including
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the Netherlands, Poland and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Barents Euro-Arctic Council groups Sweden, Denmark,
Finland, Iceland, Norway and Russia. Sweden held the chairmanship
of the council last year, and Norway this year took over the
rotating post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
