<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Post-Telecom Industry to Grow 28 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The business volume of China's
post and telecommunications sector is expected to grow 28 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Chinese Ministry of Post and
Telecommunications, China in the year will complete the
construction of a nationwide optical cable network, which, with
eight horizontal and eight vertical trunks, will link up 31
Chinese provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
The overall telephone switching capacity is to reach 128 million
lines with 17 million new lines hooking up with the network.
</P>
<P>
The country plans to develop 12 million telephone users this
year. Upon completion, 9.7 percent of the Chinese people will be
telephone owners. The rate in urban areas will be 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
An additional 10 million mobile telephone switchboards will be
installed in 1998, with eight million subscribers added.
</P>
<P>
Some 400,000 new users are expected to apply for the use of
data and multimedia services offered by the telecom service
providers.
</P>
<P>
The ministry designated the year 1998 a "Year of Quality
Services" in the hope to improve services in telephone
installation, fare payment and mail delivery.
</P>
<P>
China's post and telecom sector in 1997 registered a growth of
33 percent on 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
