<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Moves to Lower Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines is focusing its attention on bringing down commercial
banks' interest rates to around 20 percent, local press reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson has
recommended for approval by the Monetary Board the proposal of the
Bankers Association for the reopening of the 30-day repurchase and
lending window at an interest rate of one percent over the 90-day
Treasury Bill rate.
</P>
<P>
The repurchase window will allow banks to avail of cheap funds
from the Central Bank and earn an interest spread that is higher
than when they borrow from each other overnight, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added, however, that commercial banks availing of the window
will be required to reduce their overbought dollar position by 50
percent, or 5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Singson also recommended for approval another
proposal by the Bankers Association for the outright sale of
banks' government securities holdings to the Central Bank at
market rates.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped the adoption of the twin measures would enable
banks to reduce their interest rates to around 20 percent, but he
could not say how soon and by how much banks would cut their
rates.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that interest rates are not likely to go down to
their pre-devaluation level of 14 to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the depreciation of the Philippine currency of
peso since July last year, the banks' interest rates now stand at
between 25 and 30 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
