<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States believes the further withdrawal
of the Israeli troops from the West Bank is one of the important
things for the Middle East peace process to be pulled back on
track, U.S. officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton offered his view, during his talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the White House Tuesday
that the United States believed the important thing "would
be a credible withdrawal plan" for redeploying Israeli troops from
the occupied West Bank.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright reiterated the U.S. view that "in order for us
to put all the pieces of the Middle East peace process back
together, one of the important pieces is the further
redeployment." (US-Israel-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat
said Tuesday that he would ask Washington to persuade Israel to
keep its peace commitments in order to break up the Mideast peace
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
"We are not asking for the impossible, but rather for the
implementation of the agreements that we signed under the auspices
of U.S. President (Bill) Clinton at the White House," Arafat told
an Egyptian TV program.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the statement at the end of his two-day visit to
Egypt during which he held talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak on the latest developments of the Mideast peace process.
(Egypt-Arafat-Washington Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami has reiterated
that there is no need for Iran to resume ties with the United
States since Washington still adopts hegemonic policies.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA Tuesday, Khatami
made the remark Monday night while addressing a large group of
people at the mausoleum of the late spiritual leader Ayatollah
Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
"Today we do not need to have the United States at our side, we
can go ahead without the help of the United States," he said,
accusing Washington of "behaving like lords of the world and
imposing sanctions on every country." (Iran-Khatami-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos and the
opposition UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi will meet in their own
country from February 16-20.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed today by Isaias Samakuva, head of the UNITA
team in the Joint Commission of the Angolan Peace Process, in an
interview with State Radio of Angola.
</P>
<P>
He said that a high level UNITA delegation headed by General
Artur Vinama arrived here on Monday to discuss the issues related
to the summit with the government delegation. (Angola-Talks)
</P>
