<HEADLINE> Sainz Steals Lead, Makinen Tumbles Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Double Monte Carlo champion
Carlos Sainz of Spain made up ground on the withdrew of overnight
leader Tommi Makinen of Finland, leading after the second leg and
13th stage of the rally on Tuesday in Monte Carlo, Monaco.
</P>
<P>
The Spaniard, in a Toyota Corolla, led by an impressive 55
seconds ahead of Finn Juha Kankkunen, in a Ford Escort.
</P>
<P>
Makinen, chasing for his third world title en route this
season, drove his Mitsbishi Lancer, in which he won the world
title last year, out of the road three kilometers into the opening
stage of the day's seven before he pulled out of the rally.
</P>
<P>
Sainz, who won twice world championship, won the seventh stage
by 12 seconds from Kankkunen, while the latter took the eighth on
the dirty and icy patches.
</P>
<P>
1997 Monte Carlo winner Piero Liatti of Italy and Briton Colin
McRae, world champion in 1995, won the following three stages with
the Italian pocketing two.
</P>
<P>
Over the higher final two stages of the leg, Frenchman Didier
Auriol took the 12th in his Corolla and Belgian Bruno Thiry the
13th in a Ford Escort.
</P>
<P>
Makinen, who led after Monday's first leg by a comfortable one
minute and 08.5 seconds, tumbled 10 meters below the road at the
Col des Garcinets peak outside Gap. 
</P>
