<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Further Reduction of Weapons of Mass Destruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Further progress in reducing
weapons of mass destruction should be made because of the
opportunities afforded by the end of the Cold War, said United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the 1998 session of the Conference on
Disarmament (CD) which opened here Tuesday, Annan emphasized that
"nuclear disarmament must be pursued more vigorously, particularly
by nuclear-weapon states, with a view to the progressive reduction
and complete elimination of nuclear weapons at the earliest date."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief's message was read out by Vladimir Petrovsky,
his personal representative and the CD secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, I expressed serious concern at the spread of
various types of conventional weapons, especially landmines and
small arms which are extensively used in regional and sub-regional
conflicts," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
A consensus has been reached on the re-establishment of the
Department for Disarmament Affairs, Annan added.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 session of the CD is to take place in three parts with
the first part from January 20 to March 27, the second from May 11
to June 26 and the third from July 27 to September 9.
Representatives from some 60 CD member states attended Tuesday's
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
