<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Agree to Continue Efforts on Okinawa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
agreed Tuesday to continue bilateral efforts to curtail the
U.S. military presence in Japan's southernmost island prefecture of
Okinawa, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting held at the Japanese Prime Minister's official
residence, Hashimoto and Cohen reaffirmed the importance of an
agreement reached in December 1996 by the bilateral Special Action
Committee on Okinawa (SACO).
</P>
<P>
Under the SACO agreement, the U.S. agreed to return the Marine
Corps Futemma Air Station in Okinawa in five to seven years on
condition that the station's heliport functions are maintained in
some way.
</P>
<P>
In line with the accord, Tokyo selected Nago in northern
Okinawa as the best candidate for the substitute heliport, but the
government's plan has been strongly opposed by local residents.
</P>
<P>
While explaining the difficulties the SACO agreement on the
Futemma Air Station is currently facing in Nago, Hashimoto vowed
to maintain bilateral cooperation on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Cohen agreed on the importance of continued joint efforts on
the Okinawa issue.
</P>
<P>
Following Hashimoto-Cohen meeting, Japan and the United States
established a comprehensive planning mechanism to put into force
the revised Japan-U.S. guidelines on bilateral defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was initialed at a top defense meeting involving
Cohen, Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi and Defense Agency
chief Fumio Kyuma.
</P>
<P>
Cohen flew into Tokyo earlier Tuesday from Beijing on his
seven-nation Asian tour which has already taken him to Malaysia,
Indonesia, Singapore, Thailand and China. He will leave for South
Korea on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
