<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Inflation Sinks to Six-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's inflation rate
last year sank to the lowest level since 1992, said Statistics NZ
in a media release received Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The office put the consumer price index (CPI), or headline
inflation, in 1997 at 0.8 percent, the lowest since the year
ending March 1992, when it was also 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
But underlying inflation, which excludes interest rates, rose
1.6 percent in the year. Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash is
contracted by the Government to keep underlying inflation between
0 and 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts predict that in view of the low inflation,
short-term interest rates will fall within a week.
</P>
<P>
At the present, 90-day bank bill rate, the key indicator for
commercial banks to fix their interest rates, stands at around 9
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
