<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine "Comfort Women" Demand Japan's Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Five Filipino women forced into
sexual slavery by Japanese troops during World War II rejected on
Tuesday an apology and an offer of compensation money from
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, local press reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the former "comfort women" as saying that the
letter of apology, received on January 1, did not fulfill their
demands for an admission of responsibility. The letter was
returned to Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
The 1.2 million Yen (9,302 U.S. dollars) compensation package
was "unrealistic" since it was to be paid out over a five-year
period, said the women now aged between 67 and 72.
</P>
<P>
"Only an official apology accompanied by state compensation
will fulfill Japan's legal responsibility and realize justice for
us," they said.
</P>
<P>
Historians estimate that up to 200,000 women throughout Asia
were forced to supply sexual services to Japanese troops during
the war. Most of the former Filipino "comfort women" have died.
</P>
</TEXT>
