<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafter Wins in Four Sets at Australian Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- No.2 seeded Pat Rafter of
Australia held off hot-tempered American Jeff Tarango to win their
first-round match at the Australian Open tennis in Melbourne
tonight.
</P>
<P>
Tarango was warned for unsportsmanlike conduct in the fourth
set, which Rafter eventually won to take the match 7-6 (7-4), 7-6
(7-4), 6-7 (7-4), 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Tarango, who had argued several times during the match with
chair umpire Mike Morrissey, was warned after losing serve at 2-3
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
"You owe me twice and you know it," Tarango yelled at the
change of ends, also angrily holding up two fingers to stress his
point.
</P>
<P>
Tarango was referring to two tight calls in the fifth game
which went against him.
</P>
<P>
The American was then warned and he called out tournament
referee Peter Bellenger, who spoke to him before play resumed.
</P>
<P>
Tarango was banned from the 1996 Wimbledon tournament after an
infamous clash with French referee Bruno Rebeuh the year before,
the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Tarango broke back immediately after tonight's warning, but
Rafter played some brilliant shots to break the American's serve
again and take a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
He served out the match with an ace.
</P>
<P>
Rafter started the match shakily, dropping his first two serves
to trail 3-0.
</P>
<P>
But the Australian then broke back twice and held serve to
force a tie break for the first set.
</P>
<P>
Rafter dominated it and then raced to a 4-1 lead in the second
set, but this time it was Tarango's turn to fight back and force
the tiebreak.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, Last year's American Open champion, again prevailed to
take a two-set lead.
</P>
<P>
The third set went to serve, with Tarango taking a 4-0 lead in
the tiebreak and then holding off Rafter's challenge to keep the
match alive.
</P>
<P>
Rafter appeared to be flagging at this point, but lifted in the
fourth and played some brilliant shots in the decisive 11th game.
</P>
<P>
The scrappy American never gave up throughout the match and
frequently upset his better-credentialed opponent with outstanding
court coverage.
</P>
<P>
Rafter's popularity helped set an attendance record today, with
the day/night aggregate of 48,134 an all-time best.
</P>
<P>
It beat the mark of 42,120, set on day five at last year's event.
</P>
<P>
The daytime crowd of 34,789 was also the first time the Australian
Open had attracted more than 30,000 to a session.
</P>
<P>
The previous record of 29,398 had been set in yesterday's opening
session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
