<HEADLINE> Sales Resigns as HK's ASFOC President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A. de O Sales resigned here
on Tuesday from the post of the president of the Amateur Sports
Federation and Olympic Committee of Hong Kong, China.
</P>
<P>
Sales, 78, who has been the leader of the local sports'
governing body for 50 years, announced his resignation during its
monthly Council meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong has high standing in the world of sports
because of its good performance and of the fact that the Amateur
Sports Federation and Olympic Committee has been conducting its
affairs in a correct and serious way according to the regulations
of the International Olympic Committee, the Olympic Council of
Asia and other international sports organizations.
</P>
<P>
"So it's time for me to step down because of the change of
circumstances" and for personal reasons "as I must turn my
attention to my own affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The new organization will have to just carry on, but must have
working people, hard-working and serious people to develop sports
here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Fok, vice president of the Hong Kong Sports Development
Board, told reporters after the Council meeting that some friends
had suggested that he comes out to be more involved and do more
for Hong Kong's sports. He said he would consider the proposal
and might apply to run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's no longer necessary to argue about Hong Kong's
identity as the issue has been clearly settled down. Now the main
efforts should be on how to develop and improve Hong Kong's
sports," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Sales and I and all my colleagues have long contributed to
the development of Hong Kong's sports and as Hong Kong has
returned to the motherland, I think local sports should enjoy more
share of resources for its development programs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fok said that Hong Kong should take the advantage of its unique
position of being part of China as well as an international city
to further build up its reputation in international sports arena.
</P>
<P>
The Amateur Sports Federation and Olympic Committee will select
its new president on March 24, with candidates to be nominated at
least 21 days ahead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
