<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- High-profile republican delegates are threatening to oust
Ian Sinclair as chairman of the Constitutional Convention, amid
confusion over the rules and criticism of the agenda for the
historic meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's financial services sector is set for a shake-up
after insurance and investment companies National Mutual and MLC
agreed to merge to become a 51 billion Australian dollar (33
billion US dollar) financial giant that will match the AMP Society
(the largest life insurance company in the country) in size.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Labor Party (Opposition) veteran Barry Jones will
serve a record third term as ALP president after a right-wing
challenge to his position was called off Tuesday to avoid
embarrassment to opposition leader Kim Beazley.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The Cabinet Tuesday approved 300 million Australian dollars
(195 million US dollars) in trade insurance to help producers
exporting to South Korea.  
</P>
