<HEADLINE> Wall Stocks Rally Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Stocks rallied today at Wall
Street, pushing most indexes into positive territory for 1998 as
another strong day on foreign markets strengthened the confidence
of investors and some major American companies reported their
encouraging profits.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 119.57 to 7,873.12, the
first 100-point gain of the new year for the struggling blue-chip
barometer.
</P>
<P>
Other broader measures also posted big gains, with most wiping
out the remainder of their early 1998 losses, and some moving
within reach of new highs.
</P>
<P>
The Dow has erased all but 35 points of its new year's deficit,
which totaled 327 points, or 4.1 percent, slightly more than a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 644.79 million,
the 10th time in 12 sessions this year that more than 600 million
shares have changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 17.09 to 978.60, up
more than 8 points for the year and about 5 points shy of record
territory.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 8.25 to 511.92, up just 0.73 for
the year, but less than 3 points from a new record high.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 27.26 to 1,590.14, up about 20
points for the year, but still some 55 points from record levels.
</P>
<P>
Among smaller-company measures, the American Stock Exchange
composite index rose 9.38 to 673.37, and the Russell 2000 rose
5.06 to 431.31.
</P>
<P>
Before today's open, Chase Manhattan and Citicorp, the nation's
two biggest banks, posted respectable gains for the fourth
quarter, saying their troubles in Asia were offset by strength in
other business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
