<HEADLINE> South China City Focuses on Urban Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the largest city
in south China, has planned to allocate some 12.7 billion yuan
(1.59 billion U.S.dollars) for urban construction in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The plan, involving over 100 major projects, will focus on
updating the city's transportation system, cultural facility
installation and environmental protection, according to Mayor Lin
Shusen.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, an old industrial city and the capital of Guangdong
Province, has confronted with the problems of traffic congestion,
dirty streets and air pollution in recent years. These problems
have adversely affected the city's development.
</P>
<P>
Construction of a subway, the new Baiyun Airport, a ring
expressway and four large gymnasiums in the city is ongoing,
according to Lin.
</P>
<P>
A number of cultural projects, including a museum, a theater
and an art gallery, will be built.
</P>
<P>
An afforestation project will also be carried out on 200 ha
of land in Guganzhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
