<HEADLINE> US: Further Withdrawal Important for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States believes
the further withdrawal of the Israeli troops from the West Bank is
one of the important things for the Middle East peace process to
be pulled back on track, U.S. officials said today.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton offered his view, during his talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the White House
today, that the United States believed the important thing "would
be a credible withdrawal plan" for redeploying Israeli troops from
the occupied West Bank, a senior U.S. official said after U.S. and
Israeli leaders met.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin also said Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright reiterated the U.S. view that "in order
for us to put all the pieces of the Middle East peace process back
together, one of the important pieces is the further
redeployment."
</P>
<P>
He said Albright had a breakfast with the Israeli prime
minister, and then Clinton had a meeting with him, that lasted
about 90 minutes, in which the secretary of state also attended.
</P>
<P>
Albright "felt the meetings were businesslike and that
substantive issues were fully explored and fully addressed," Rubin
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States had hoped that Israel could offer a
sizable and credible pullback of the West Bank, that was helpful
in pushing the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
"With respect to further redeployment, we do believe that it
needs to take place in a way that it is credible, that the size
needs to be significant," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said after his talks with Clinton that there was no
breakthrough for any redeployment of the Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
"We are now looking for a joint formula to advance the peace
process.... No agreement has yet been formulated," he told Israel
television in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Rubin did not disclose what size of pullback the United States
believed was needed for pulling together the pieces of the peace
process. But according to some reports, the United States proposed
a 12 percent of the West Bank to be handed over to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu was said to have brought a modest offer of 9
percent of the Israeli-occupied West Bank to the Palestinians,
which certainly falls short of U.S. expectations and even far away
from the demand of the Palestinian leader Yassar Arafat, who said
Israel should yield 80 or 90 percent of the territory and half of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Before his talks with Netanyahu, Clinton indicated he was not
planning to pressure the Israeli leader on the issue of
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
"I think what we ought to talk about is what both sides can do
now," he said at a photo session with Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would have "a detailed, frank, good discussion"
with the Israeli leader. "We are going to work hard to make
progress," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth time that Clinton met with Netanyahu. Clinton,
claiming to be the sponsor of the Middle East peace process, has
not been very happy with Netanyahu constantly turning a deaf ear
to U.S. repeated warning over Israel's moves that were in
contradiction with Oslo agreements.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Israel's unilateral action of establishing
Jewish settlements in the West Bank, Rubin said the U.S. view was
that this kind of unilateral action could only "make it difficult
to create an environment for the negotiations and make it harder
to create success in those negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians have
suspended for over 10 months because of Israel's decision to build
Jewish housing units in Arab East Jerusalem and its refusal to
withdraw from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
After failures of U.S. mediations by its envoy Dennis Ross and
Albright, Clinton has to come out to deal directly with Netanyahu
and Arafat, whom Clinton will meet Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
