<HEADLINE> BBC World Service Goes on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- BBC World Service in English is
now available in audio on the internet following a deal with the
U.S. internet company AudioNet, the BBC announced today in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Internet users all over the world can now tune in to BBC World
Service round the clock every day via the website
www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice or www.audionet.com/bbc, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Caroline Thomson, deputy managing director of BBC World
Service, said that BBC World Service sees online as an
increasingly important way of reaching listeners alongside
shortwave, FM and AM.
</P>
<P>
The deal with AudioNet is part of the self-help strategy to
offset delivery costs, Thomson said.
</P>
<P>
BBC World Service now broadcasts in English and 43 other
languages to over 140 million listeners around the world. The
audience in English is estimated at 35 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
