<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Farmers Protest at Downing Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- British farmers demonstrated at
Downing Street here Tuesday, demanding compensation for strength
of the pound and beef ban which are crippling their industry.
</P>
<P>
The farmers also delivered to 10 Downing Street a petition of
500,000 signatures, urging the government to recognize "the
special needs of people who live and work in the rural areas".
</P>
<P>
Before going to the Downing Street, thousands of farmers
gathered at the parliament, protesting over the beef ban and the
sale of cheap imported meat.
</P>
<P>
At a rally, National Farmers' Union President Sir David Naish
urged the government to take up the offer of compensation offered
to farmers by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"Never since the Second World War has such pressure been put on
the providers of the nation's food," he said.
</P>
<P>
The strong pound makes British food more expensive to sell
abroad and reduces the value of EU subsidies, an important part of
farmers' income.
</P>
<P>
Farmers are also feeling beleaguered by the EU's ban on British
beef exports, imposed following fears of "mad cow disease".
</P>
</TEXT>
