<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Defends Its Ambassador to Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
today rejected accusations by a former U.S. diplomat that the
American ambassador to Ireland, Jean Kennedy Smith, is an "ardent
apologist" of the Irish Republic Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
In his autobiography, Former Ambassador Raymond Seitz blamed
Smith for what he says is an all-time low in Anglo-American
relations.
</P>
<P>
"It became obvious she wanted to promote the reunification of
both parts of Ireland, even if one of the parts happened to lie in
the United Kingdom," an Associated Press report quoted Seitz as
saying in his book.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing, State Department spokesman
James Rubin said that he has not seen the book by Seitz but
defended Smith's performance in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
"The charge that Ambassador Jean Kennedy Smith is an apologist
for the IRA is ridiculous," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Seitz, who served in London from 1991 to 1994, also charged
that the Clinton administration leaked secret information about
Northern Ireland to IRA sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
"The president's involvement in creating the conditions for a
cease-fire and promoting the peace process has led us to a point
where everyone is sitting down and talking about peace right now,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"We have moved far beyond the situation when Ambassador Seitz
was there, and sometimes people on the other side of a policy
battle, you know, wish things weren't true that were true," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
