<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street rose
sharply today, propelled by another strong day on foreign markets,
and better company profit.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average jumped 119.57 points to
7,873.12, slicing its losses for 1998 to just 35 points, or less
than 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 639.02 million shares, as against 665.84
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 17.09 to 978.60,
about 5 points shy of record territory, and the NYSE composite
index rose 8.25 to 511.92, less than 3 points from a new high.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 27.26 to 1,590.14, the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 9.38 to 673.37, and the
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.06 to 431.31.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's big gainers also included investor favorites such as
Disney, General Electric, and IBM, which was due to report its
latest results after today's close.
</P>
<P>
Japanese stocks rose for a fifth straight session as government
ministers reiterated Tokyo's commitment to economic stimulus
measures.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose 2 percent in Indonesia, but the Indonesian currency
fell to a new low. 
</P>
</TEXT>
