<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares up on Strong Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
opened weaker on worries over Asia Tuesday, but later managed to
end higher, supported by the dollar's strength, bid fever in
pharmaceuticals and steady gains in U.S. shares.
</P>
<P>
British shares on the London market had been pulled both ways
during the session before ending at 5,278.2, up 4.6 points or
barely 0.1 percent in heavy volume as the market tracked Wall
Street's performance.
</P>
<P>
The market got a strong boost from gains in the drug sector on
confirmation that Britain's SmithKline Beecham was in merger talks
with U.S. group American Home Products.
</P>
<P>
However, dealers said that an early drug sector-led rally
tailed off as investors took profits.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, worries about sterling's strength and possible
interest rate rises weighed on market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares ended almost half a percent higher,
thanks to the still firm dollar and market expectations of Wall
Street gains.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that mildly better Asian markets also helped share
prices. The DAX-30 index closed 22.97 points up at 4,307.91.
</P>
<P>
French stocks in Paris ended higher for the sixth session in a
row after a slow start as technical difficulties forced the market
to open two hours late.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index finished the session above the 3,000-point
level at 3,008.34, a rise of 21.39 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
