<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Minister Cleared of Breaking Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Standards and Privileges
Committee agreed today there is "no case to answer" against
Treasury Minister Geoffrey Robinson.
</P>
<P>
The committee concluded that Robinson had not "breached the
rules of the House" by failing to register his links with an
offshore trust.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards Sir Gordon Downey said
there was no case for saying Robinson had breached rules on
registration of interests over the Guernsey-registered Orion
Trust.
</P>
<P>
Opposition spokesman Peter Lilley wrote to Downey in December,
asking him to investigate the affair.
</P>
<P>
But the committee said that although Robinson did not break the
rule, he should consult Standards Commissioner Downey if a doubt
should arise, instead of seeking his personal advisers for help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
