<DOCNO> XIE19980121.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Urges US to Apply Pressure on Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat said Tuesday that he would ask Washington
to persuade Israel to keep its peace commitments in order to break
up the Mideast peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
"We are not asking for the impossible, but rather for the
implementation of the agreements that we signed under the auspices
of U.S. President (Bill) Clinton at the White House," Arafat told
an Egyptian TV program.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the statement at the end of his two-day visit to
Egypt during which he held talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak on the latest developments of the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
He left here Tuesday morning for Paris to drum up support of
the European leaders before meeting Thursday with Clinton in
Washington in a make-or-break attempt to save the faltering
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. wants Israel to withdraw from more West Bank territory
and freeze Jewish settlements, and the Palestinians to crack down
harder on violence as a prelude to jump-starting talks on a final
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Israeli former Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin signed
an interim agreement granting the Palestinians limited autonomy in
1993, paving the way for the following Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
"The agreements were not only signed by the Palestinians and
the Israelis, but also by President Hosni Mubarak, King Hussein of
Jordan, the U.S., Russia, the European Union and Norway," Arafat
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Mideast peace process has had hard time ever since
the government of Benjamin Netanyahu came to power in June 1996,
the Palestinian leader lamented.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinians cannot accept any kind of formula
other than the one that is based on the UN resolutions and the
land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the Israeli troops have to withdraw from all the
occupied Palestinian territories when it comes to the final
settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader has warned that if the peace process
fails, the Palestinians are open to all options, including a
return to Palestinian uprisings in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Arafat talks on Monday focused on the ideas the
Palestinian leader is expected to present to Clinton in a bid to
push forward peace talks that ground to a halt last March after
Israel started to build a new settlement in Arab East Jerusalem
and Palestinian militants later responded with suicide bombings.
</P>
<P>
The two Arab leaders also discussed the Israeli plan to keep
control over strategic areas in the West Bank in a final peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which has in the past helped mediate between Israelis
and the Palestinians, has repeatedly urged the Clinton
administration to force its Israeli ally to honor signed peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab officials and commentators see the talks in
Washington as a last chance to break the 10-month-old impasse and
demand that Washington induce Israel to modify its hard line on
peace.
</P>
<P>
After his talks with Clinton and U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Arafat is expected to meet Mubarak in Cairo
again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
