<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The National Bank of Kuwait Tuesday declared a
73.5 million Kuwait Dinar (242.55 million U.S. dollars) net
profits in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The bank's Board Chairman, Mohammad Abdelrahman Al-Bahr, said
in a press release that all bank activities proved very productive
last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that consolidated balance sheet aggregate was up to
4,118 million dinars (13.59 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The bank, the largest commercial bank in Kuwait, was
established in 1952.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Nearly 2.3 million tourists visited Israel last
year, a drop of 3 percent compared to 1996, according to figures
released Tuesday by the Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS) and
Tourism Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the decline was actually less than what had
been predicted, despite the three major suicide bombings attacks
in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem last year.
</P>
<P>
"The predictions had been for a catastrophe, but after all the
terror attacks this year, the number was more or less the same as
last year," ministry spokeswoman Orly Doron said.
</P>
<P>
The CBS said there had been a major decline in the number of
incoming tourists during the first half of 1996 following a series
of terror bombings launched early that year by Islamic
militants.
</P>
<P>
But this leveled off during the second half of 1996, and the
number of visitors remained stable through last year, it added.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The World Bank has granted to Lebanon a loan of 63
million U.S. dollars to help boost the country's technical
training and education, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
The loan agreement was signed recently by the bank's
representative Vasilios Demetriou and Lebanese Minister of
Professional and Technical Education Farouq Al-Barbir.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to support technical education,
strengthen administration and vocational programs, renovate
and enlarge existing schools in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
